<SECOND>AM-Prison Crash,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Filed In Miami Helicopter Escape Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A convict serving a life sentence for drug smuggling and the helicopter pilot who tried to spring him from prison but crashed were charged Tuesday with conspiracy and attempted escape. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON>, a nationally known powerboat racer serving a life sentence for marijuana smuggling, and sea-urchin diver <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, both 34, were charged Tuesday afternoon as they recuperated at <ORGANIZATION> Jackson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> crashed Monday as his two-seater Bell helicopter snagged on a 14-foot wire security fence around the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> during an attempt to take <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> out of a recreation yard. <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> suffered a compound fracture to his left ankle and was listed in satisfactory condition. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, with two broken legs and injuries to the head, neck and back, was in good condition. A court appearance has not been scheduled yet. `` <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> started to take off from the compound with <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> hanging to the helicopter skids attempting to enter the cockpit,'' marshal <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Figmik </PERSON> wrote in the arrest affidavit. `` The helicopter's blades became entangled in a security fence and the helicopter crashed.'' Authorities say <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, who most recently lived on the <LOCATION> Oregan </LOCATION> coast, was an amateur pilot just learning to fly helicopters. In December, he paid $ 35,000 in cash for the chopper from a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> flight instructor and got four hours of flying instruction.
