<HEAD>Dartmouth Students Appeal Federal Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> students have appealed the dismissal of their lawsuit against the college, which they claim discriminated against them because of their race and conservative beliefs, a lawyer said Tuesday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> last month dismissed a lawsuit filed by the three white students, who were suspended after a February 1988 classroom confrontation with <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, a black music professor. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Quilhot </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, worked for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative off-campus weekly newspaper that had described <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> as part of `` <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION>'s Dynamic Duo of Mediocrity.'' They accused Cole of grabbing Quilhot by the arm and breaking the flash on his camera during the encounter, but a campus disciplinary board found them guilty of harassing Cole, and they were suspended in March 1988. `` It's in our best interest to go through with the appeal,'' <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> said Tuesday. The student's lawyer, <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said the three disagreed with <PERSON> Devine </PERSON>'s ruling that, even if the students demonstrated that they were treated unfairly because of their conservative politics and affiliation with the Review, they would not have a case under the racial discrimination statutes they cited. The appeal was filed Monday in the 1st U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGA