<HEAD>Principal Vetoes Article About Pregnant Valedictorian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high school principal has pulled a story from the school newspaper about the senior class valedictorian, a straight-A honors student who is pregnant with her second child. <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, principal of <ORGANIZATION> Jack </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, vetoed an article by a student reporter about <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mae </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, who is five months pregnant and carries a full load of classes, including physics, calculus and economics. The story, titled `` Against all odds ... Student becomes valedictorian despite motherhood,'' details Miss <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>'s first pregnancy, how she was shuffled among relatives after her mother died and her stepfather deserted her and eight siblings, and her dream of a `` middle-class home and a middle-class life.'' Miss <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, who spends two to five hours a night with her books, has no one to baby-sit her 18-month-old daughter, <PERSON> Terrisha </PERSON> <PERSON> KeAndrea </PERSON>. She keeps the child occupied with paper and a pencil, and `` she writes while I write.'' Miss <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, 17, has been accepted to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> and has two scholarships. She plans to major in chemical engineering. A school reporter first tried to do a story about Miss <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> last year after she was spotted on a cold, rainy day standing at a bus stop, holding an umbrella over her daughter, while studying a math text. A school official blocked the story. According to newspaper editor <PERSON> Shuronda </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> rejected the story Thursday when she submitted the newspaper for approval. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> told reporters Tuesday that he thought the article was too personal to be printed in the newspaper, and <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> Superintendent <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> agreed. `` In his judgment, the article was too highly personal, sensitive to the young lady, and he did not permit it to be published,'' she said. `` I have read the article myself, and I will further tell you that I would have made the same decision.'' Miss <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said the newspaper staff offered to edit the story to satisfy <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, but the offer was rejected. He also rejected a request to run a blank space or the word `` censored'' in place of the story. Although Miss <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> has worried the school officials will bar her from giving her valedictory address on graduation night June 10, Ms. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> said she will be allowed to speak and participate in any graduation activity.
