<HEAD>France Sends Arms To Cambodian Resistance For The First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for the first time has sent arms to guerrillas fighting <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, newspapers today quoted a senior Thai officer as saying. The shipments are going to the forces of Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, president of the three-party guerrilla coalition, said Gen. <PERSON> Sunthorn </PERSON> <PERSON> Kongsompong </PERSON>, the armed forces chief of staff. The latest shipment arrived a few days ago, <PERSON> Sunthorn </PERSON> was quoted as saying Tuesday, according to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bangkok </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, Thai <PERSON> Rath </PERSON> and other newspapers. The arms are being shipped through Thai territory to the guerrillas on the Thai-Cambodian border, the newspapers said. The reports said <PERSON> Sunthorn </PERSON> dismissed concerns the aid may affect <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s plan to and withdraw all its troops from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by Sept. 30, ending a 10-year military occupation. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has demanded a simultanous halt in outside military aid to the guerrillas. <PERSON> Sunthorn </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s main source of foreign aid, will continue to pressure <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> for a pullout. The resistance receives the bulk of its weapons from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The strongest <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> resistance group, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, seized power in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in 1975 and over the next four years killed hundreds of thousands of people as they tried to create a primitive agrarian society. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded in December 1978 and ousted the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> has been a strong diplomatic supporter of the resistance and has played host to talks between <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>, the prime minister of the Vietnamese-installed government in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. The French made <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> a protectorate in 1864 and granted independence in 1953, with <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> as its leader.
