 A <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 en route to <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> turned back to <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION> today when an engine overheated soon after takeoff, the airline said. The plane landed normally with one of its four engines shut down, said <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodge </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s manager for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>. He said the pilot shut down the engine down when he realized it was overheating. The plane was carrying 173 passenger and 18 crew members. The passengers were transferred to an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zealand </ORGANIZATION> flight, which left soon after. `` It was a non-emergency. The pilot did n't have to dump fuel,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Merlini </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s manager for <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. United has had a rash of problems in recent weeks. In February, a cargo door blew out on a jumbo flying the 811 route from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION>, sweeping nine people to their deaths. Late last month, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> 747 turned back to <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION> 45 minutes after takeoff when an engine failed, and earlier this month a jumbo damaged its undercarriage during a heavy landing at <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> on the flight from <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION>.
