<HEAD>Thatcher Says She Survived Assassination Attempt By Chance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> was quoted today as saying an aide who demanded a policy decision at 2 a.m. probably saved her life in 1984 when the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> blew up the hotel where she was staying. She was quoted as saying in an interview with Readers Digest that she was about to go bed after working in her hotel suite until 2:45 a.m. when her private secretary, <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, insisted upon a decision. She had been up polishing her keynote address to her <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s annual conference. `` He thrust a set of papers into my hand and while I was reading them, the explosion went off,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> was quoted as saying. `` Had I not been reviewing those papers, I would have gone straight into the bathroom. Another person whose bathroom was a few floors above mine had done exactly that and was virtually blown to bits.'' The Oct. 12, 1984, explosion wrecked the hotel where Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and most of her Cabinet were staying for the convention in <LOCATION> Brighton </LOCATION>, killing five people and injuring 30. The <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> is fighting to push the British out of <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, join it with the <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and set up an all-Ireland socialist state.
