<HEAD>Fed Agency Backs Tennessee Bridge Inspection Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal agency defended the state's bridge inspection program, despite the collapse of two <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> bridges in two weeks `` They have a good program with solid routine,'' <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Deggs </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s state office, said Tuesday. Eight persons died in the collapse of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 51 bridge over the <LOCATION> Hatchie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> on April 1. A teen-ager was killed when a railroad bridge collapsed near <LOCATION> Oliver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> in east <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> on Saturday. An inspector four years ago urged repairs to the east <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> bridge, but authorities never recommended that it be closed. An inspection of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 51 bridge also warned of problems.
