<SECOND>PM-Precious Woodcarving,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woodcarver Is Famous At Last</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A little-known early 16th-century German sculptor, <PERSON> Niclaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Weckmann </PERSON> the Elder, became a major figure in art history when a woodcarving of his sold at auction for $ 423,000, <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s said `` The price was a very high one for such a work,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Wrey </PERSON>, a spokesman for the auction house, after the sale Tuesday of the Weckmann's Adoration of the <ORGANIZATION> Magi </ORGANIZATION>. The seller was described only as a continental nobleman. The buyer was anonymous but <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Avery </PERSON>, the firm's head of sculpture, said the work `` may be going back to south <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which would be appropriate as that was <PERSON> Weckmann </PERSON>'s homeland.'' The limewood carving, more than five feet tall and four feet wide, was once part of an altarpiece and depicts the wise men presenting their gifts to the infant <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>. `` It had been in the private chapel of a noble family in <LOCATION> Styria </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> -RRB- for 100 years or so and probably no one else saw it,'' <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> said. `` If we knew where it had been for the 300 years before that it would been even more costly as a complete antique provenance adds to value,'' he said. <PERSON> Weckmann </PERSON> lived from about 1460 to 1520. His works were attributed to other artists until 1968, when he was identified as one of the greatest sculptors working in the town of Ulm around 1500. <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> said he was so impressed by the unsigned carving when it arrived for auction that he asked for a study of it from <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaedler </PERSON>, chief curator of sculpture at the National Bavarian Museum in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>. `` Schaedler is the expert on <LOCATION> Weckmann </LOCATION> and he attibuted it to him on grounds of style and type. It is one of the largest and most splendid pieces of Gothic German wood sculpture to be auctioned in recent times,'' <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> added. As nothing identified as <PERSON> Weckmann </PERSON>'s work had been auctioned before, <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s said they were uncertain how to estimate the carving's price, at first setting it at $ 172,000 and then thinking it might go up to $ 344,000.
</TEXT>
