<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON>, <PERSON> Liza </PERSON> <PERSON> Minnelli </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> received a rapturous welcome from a star-studded audience at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s Royal <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> for the first of five sell-out concerts. Police outside the hall had to erect barriers to hold back crowds jostling for a glimpse of the stars at Tuesday night's show. Inside, the audience of 5,200 including <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoskins </PERSON>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caine </PERSON>, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Windsor </PERSON> and many other British show business personalities sat toe-tapping and cheering in near continuous applause. The five Royal <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> concerts by the three American stars are the start of the British leg of a 23-concert world tour billed as `` The Ultimate Event.''
