<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Impressionist <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> says he usually imitates the stars of yesteryear because the voices of today's celebrities lack character and can not be easily distinguished. <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said method-acting has replaced the melodrama that actors once lent to their speech. `` There are no more <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> Greenstreets, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorres </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cagneys </PERSON> or <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewarts </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON>, who is appearing in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> through May 1. `` If you took three of the old-timers and put them behind a door and let them talk you can tell which is which,'' <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said. `` But today you put three actors in that room and you ca n't tell them apart _ except for <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarzenegger </PERSON>.''
