<NOTE>Eds: A version of the following item moving on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> manager <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> insists he has kept most of his baseball memorabilia, but admits he sold the bat he used in 1985 to break <PERSON> Ty </PERSON> <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON>'s record. Rose sold the bat, along with a Corvette he received from <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> owner <PERSON> Marge </PERSON> <PERSON> Schott </PERSON>, to his insurance agent, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolter </PERSON>, for $ 175,000. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> still owns the bat he used for his 4,256 th and final hit, which he said he considers more significant than the one he used for No 4,192, which broke <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON>'s record. `` I've got the bat that broke the record _ it's 4,256,'' said <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>. `` The last hit I got is the record. And it will be the record until somebody gets 4,257.'' <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> put his three World Series championship rings on display Monday to counter what he says are erroneous reports that he gave his 1975 World Series championship ring to a convicted <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> bookmaker. A <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> newspaper reported Sunday that <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> gave the ring to bookmaker <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Cambra </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Somerset </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, as payment for a gambling debt. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> said the 1975 ring that <PERSON> Cambra </PERSON> has is a replica that <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> had authorized for him. The baseball commissioner announced last month he was investigating allegations involving <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, reportedly his gambling activities and whether he has bet on baseball games.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> is getting married next month after a long romance with a woman he met at a gas station. `` He said he liked my truck,'' said <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, 26, of their chance meeting at a <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> station on <LOCATION> Sunset </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boulevard </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> several years ago. <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, 42, a rising star of movies and television, pulled up in his black Porsche while Miss <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said she drove her `` old pickup truck with a bale of hay in the back.'' `` He said he was thinking of getting a truck and he liked mine ... a really bad line,'' said Miss <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, a co-owner of an import business. `` I mean I had about as much need for a truck as a platypus has for jumping shoes,'' <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> recalled during a stop in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> this week to preview `` My Name is <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> W </PERSON>,'' a made-for-TV movie about the founder of Alcoholics Anonymous that will be broadcast April 30 on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>. The couple already has moved the date of the wedding several times and has yet to commit to an exact date or location. It will be the second marriage for <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> but the first for Miss <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>. `` I always let my car go right down to empty now because its good luck to me, obviously,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Minnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pearl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> is moving to <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Opryland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> theme park from the city's Music Row area. The new museum will open Saturday, <LOCATION> Opryland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> officials said Tuesday. The comedian and country music star is known for her high-pitched greeting, `` Howdeee!'' and her hat, which sports a $ 1.98 price tag. Pearl, whose real name is <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON>, is a native of <LOCATION> Centerville </LOCATION>. She has been a cast regular in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>'s Grand Ole Opry since 1940.
