<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> is urging Californians to listen to their mothers. The governor joined <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallone </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holt </ORGANIZATION>, the mothers of actors <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallone </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cher </PERSON>, in kicking off a campaign on Tuesday to promote ride sharing and van-pool programs to help unclog freeways. But he was a little late because of traffic congestion. The campaign will feature the theme of rather universal motherly sayings. One advertisement depicts a woman who says: `` We're not the first one to try to talk some sense into you about sharing.'' Other celebrity moms taking part include <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, mother of comic <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, mother of <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lakers </ORGANIZATION> basketball star <PERSON> Earvin </PERSON> `` Magic'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. `` Your mother, as this -LRB- campaign -RRB- says, always told you to share and it was good advice then and I think it's very good advice now, and it's going to help us to meet our transportation challenges,'' <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> said <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> is the sixth-largest economic power in the world but each day workers lose about 400,000 hours of productivity while stuck in traffic. Last year, 22.4 million vehicles were in the state and there will be 23.8 million by the century's end. There is an average of 1.2 persons per vehicle in peak hours, but congestion could be eliminated if that improved to just 1.4 per vehicle, <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> got little attention when he introduced a bill to designate an official state dog, but now the `` Plott'' has thickened. The Senate Rules Committee quickly endorsed the bill to make the <PERSON> Plott </PERSON> hound <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s official dog. <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON>, a 10-year-old <PERSON> Plott </PERSON> owned by former Rep. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, wagged her tail in silent approval. `` All other breeds pale in comparison,'' said <PERSON> Swain </PERSON>, a Democrat who said the hound is the only dog indigenous to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. It's a favorite of mountain bear hunters, he said. `` It's the only dog I think would be proper for a state dog,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> told reporters after the meeting Tuesday. `` You talk about a <PERSON> Plott </PERSON>, you're talking about the <ORGANIZATION> Kit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carsons </ORGANIZATION>, the <PERSON> Davy </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocketts </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Boones </PERSON> of the dog world,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. `` They were frontier people, they went out hunting and lived by their instincts ... and they were from western <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>.'' The Plott hound is a descendant of a German breed used for boar hunting, <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. An immigrant named <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Plott </PERSON> brought it to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> in the mid-1700s. The Plott hound is an officially registered breed, <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. The typical <PERSON> Plott </PERSON> has brown-black coloring and weighs about 75 pounds. `` I think without any question it has all the qualities of a good <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolinian </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. `` He's l