<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Missouri <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed a bill making the 250-million-year-old remains of a plantlike animal the official state fossil. But some senators objected to spending time on the matter with a May 12 adjournment and several major bills pending. `` Is it any coincidence that you are trying to make the state fossil a spineless animal?'' Sen. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> asked Tuesday. `` What's next Perhaps the bat will be the state bird because it's blind.'' The state bird is the bluebird. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> said the crinoid fossil bill `` reflects the quality of legislation so far this session.'' He said he was concerned the headlines would read, `` <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> spends afternoon making spineless wimp the state fossil.'' But the bill's sponsor, Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, called the measure an important civics lesson for an eighth-grade science class in his district that first proposed it. `` Now they've seen an idea from their classroom go through both chambers for a possible signing by the governor,'' he said. Crinoids, commonly known as sea lillies, flourished 250 million years ago when most of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> was covered by shallow seas. They are found throughout the state, mainly in limestone deposits.
