<SECOND>AM-Pap Lab,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Closed Lab told To Pay For Millions Of New Pap Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State health officials ordered a laboratory to offer to pay for repeat Pap smear tests for more than 3 million women diagnosed as cancer-free after learning the lab's error rate was greater than 20 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pathology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Tarzana </LOCATION>, which has performed 3.3 million Pap smears over the past five years, was ordered closed last week after a state audit showed an error rate of 21.2 percent among 1,103 tests selected at random. `` It was a sloppy operation,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kizer </PERSON>, state health services director. `` It was totally unacceptable that they had such a high error rate.'' The lab, which also worked under the name <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diagnostic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, processed nearly 700,000 smears last year, more than half of all of the tests in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Pap smears from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> were processed at the company's <LOCATION> Tarzana </LOCATION> area lab. In its order delivered to the lab Monday, the health department said all women in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and other states who had received reports indicating no abnormalities from either Central Pathology or Central Diagnostic within the last five years needed to be offered the opportunity for a repeat Pap smear. The lab, which closed Monday, was given 30 days to contact the women and recommend they see their doctors about retaking the tests elsewhere. Central Pathology said in a statement it was `` a 27-year-old facility with a perfect inspection record to this point'' and that it had recently instituted what it called `` the most stringent quality-control standards in the nation.'' The Pap smear, which costs about $ 25, is a routine test used to detect cervical cancer and other medical abnormalities. The industry average for misdiagnosing Pap smears is about 5 percent, but some pathologists said top labs make even fewer mistakes. <PERSON> Kizer </PERSON> said state officials plan to inspect 10 other Pap smear laboratories within the next six weeks. He did not identify them. `` We need to get an idea of the other labs' error rates and set some kind of standard,'' <PERSON> Kizer </PERSON> said.
