<HEAD>Air Pollution Bill Aims at Broader Variety of Toxics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sponsors of a compromise bill to control airborne toxic chemicals say they expect stiff opposition, despite growing information on poisons in the nation's air. `` This bill will be critized by some for going too far, and by others who do n't think it has gone far enough,'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, said Tuesday after he and 11 other senators introduced the legislation. The bipartisan and diverse group said their language remains subject to hard bargaining, but emphasized they have a consensus on how to control the estimated 2.7 billion pounds of poisonous chemicals released into the atmosphere each year. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, in its first such compilation, said April 12 that the toxic air emissions are among more than 22 billion pounds of toxic wastes sent into the air, water and land each year. The legislation to control toxic emissions into the atmosphere represents a major compromise for lawmakers pushing for new clean air legislation this year. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> clean air sponsors said they will introduce the other components of their legislation in coming months: proposals to bring metropolitan areas in compliance with air quality standards, and language to control acid rain. The air toxics compromise would require companies emitting 10 tons or more of any airborne toxic chemical to install the best available control technology. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> would set emissions standards for industries releasing the chemicals. But to encourage polluters to make immediate and large-scale reductions, they would be granted exemptions if they used technology that achieves a 90 percent cutback in emissions by the end of 1992. If technology did not achieve the required reduction, a company would have to meet tough emissions limits based on a chemical's risk of causing cancer or other illnesses The legislation would replace a system that has regulated only seven toxic chemicals out of nearly 300 emitted into the air. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> is currently required to assess the risk of each chemical, and then develop chemical-by-chemical emissions standards designed to protect public health, with an ample margin of safety. The assessment for each chemical takes several years. And when the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has made proposals, the agency has been sued on grounds it went too far _ or not far enough. The bill also would direct <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to establish a national urban air toxics program to reduce the release of toxic chemicals from motor vehicles, wood stoves, dry cleaners and gas stations. In a provision to prevent catastrophic accidents, the bill would require <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to list 50 extremely hazardous substances. Facilities handling those materials would have to complete reviews to identify potential accidents. A <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> would be established to investigate accidents and make recommendations for preventive measures. Sen. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>, D-Mont., the manager of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> clean air legislation this year, told reporters, `` There is a public health crisis that will worsen if we do n't act. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Barks </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, said the environmental groups in the organization believe the bill needs improvements. He said that under the bill the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> could take between five and 13 years to set standards for emission reduction for polluters who fail to qualify for the exemption. That timetable is too long, he said. Announcing the compromise were Sens. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, R-Minn.; <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-R.I. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Quentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Burdick </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON>, D-Conn., and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON>
