<HEAD>Statue Atop Capitol Set for a Facelift</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rain, lightning and 125 years have taken such a toll on the giant bronze Statue of Freedom atop the Capitol dome that it will be removed _ probably by helicopter _ and restored, the Capitol architect says. The operation will leave a large hole in the top of the lantern which supports the statue on top of the dome. The hole will be fitted with a temporary cover to keep out rain during the six-month long, $ 250,000 restoration project, according to Architect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>. But <PERSON> White </PERSON> said the iron dome itself is in excellent condition and needs no major repairs. The 14,985-pound figure which rises 19 feet six inches from the top of the soaring dome is a symbolic cast-bronze image of a female warrior draped in flowing robes and clasping a sheathed sword. It has been a Capitol symbol since its head, the last of five sections, was hoisted aloft and bolted in place on Dec. 2, 1863. `` It has n't been touched since that time,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. `` When we had the dome repainted last summer we confirmed that the statue is in very serious condition.'' White said cracks had developed in some of the interior fastenings of the statue and that an exterior chunk of its robes fell out last year. The statue consists of five separate pieces of cast bronze bolted together and attached to a cast-iron base. `` The whole thing is in really bad condition,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. `` Bronze does deteriorate.'' In preparation for removing the statue a protective cage will be built around it, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said and added: `` We'll probably take it down by helicopter.'' The project could begin soon although no firm date has been set. The statue is the finishing flourish of the soaring dome which was completed during the middle of the Civil War. Although the iron of which it is crafted could have been used for the war effort, President <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> ordered work on the dome to continue as a symbol that the national union of states was also continuing. Many of the 15 million tourists who see the statue from a distance mistakenly believe it depicts an American Indian because of its elaborate headdress. Actually, the statue's head is covered by a helmet circled with stars and topped with a crest composed of an eagle's head and decorative feathers. White disclosed the renovation project at a ceremony launching a multimillion-dollar fund-raising effort seeking private donations for restoration work at the Capitol and to create a fund to buy art works associated with its past. In another project, the parking lot which has covered the Capitol's East Plaza since the beginning of the automotive age will be closed and the space filled with decorative stone paving. Two marble fountains, carved during <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s beautification campaign in the late 1960s but never installed because of a lack of funds, will be placed in the center of the plaza The newly created <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> will coordinate the fund raising and restoration under the direction of Former Postmaster General <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON>. <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> said the aim of the new organization will be similar to that of the foundations created to refurbish <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the president's guest house, and to acquire historic objects for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s reception rooms. The commission also will receive half the profits from the sale of special coins to be issued later in the year to commemorate the bicentennial of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> said the first fund-raising effort will be a bicentennial banquet on June 20, which is intended to raise at least $ 1.5 million.
</TEXT>
