ith his proposal to expand capital gains tax breaks that would be enjoyed predominantly by wealthy Americans. `` The president ought to have as much concern for the poor as he does for the rich,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. The conferees said they hope to have a final product in about two weeks and indicated it would be stripped of a number of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> amendments unrelated to the minimum wage, including one that would raise the outside earnings limit for Social Security recipients. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has repeatedly said the only minimum wage bill he will accept is his own, an offer to raise the minimum from its current level of $ 3.35 an hour to $ 4.25 by January 1992, provided employers can pay all new workers less than the minimum for up to six months. Both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> measures would raise the minimum wage to $ 4.55 by October 1991 and allow a `` sub-minimum'' to be paid to some newly hired workers for just two months. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said that if no compromise is reached, he is considering a number of other approaches to raising the minimum wage, including a simple one-year increase of the base wage instead of the incremental boosts contained in the current measures.
