<HEAD>Soviets: Mir Being Unmanned to Save Money, No Technical Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after graf 3 beginning `His comments ...' to
ADD Blagov saying Mir's batteries having some problems. Picks up graf 4
pvs, `Blagov said ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a cost-cutting move, the Soviets are bringing their cosmonauts home from their space station Mir next week and leaving it unmanned until August, the station's deputy flight director says. <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said no technical problems had cropped up in the 3-year-old orbiting complex that is the showcase of the Soviet space program. His comments Tuesday came a day after the magazine <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Week </ORGANIZATION> and Space Technology reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that Mir had developed a serious electrical power problem. Mir's solar batteries, <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said, were experiencing some power loss but that it was within expected levels and was not causing any problem. <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said plans to keep Soviets aboard the station continuously were abandoned for several reasons. `` By this action, we are of course economizing some sum which can be used for other purposes,'' he said by telephone from the <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kaliningrad </LOCATION>, north of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. He did not identify the other purposes, but the public has called for the untold millions of rubles spent on space to be diverted toward ending chronic shortages of consumer goods and food. <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said Soviet scientists were swamped analyzing information gathered from Mir, which was launched Feb. 20, 1986. They now must pause to review `` what we have accomplished and decide what's next. Tentative plans call for a module the same size as Mir to be attached to the station at year's end, and until then there is no need for a crew, <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said. A launching of a replacement crew originally scheduled for today has been canceled. Cosmonauts <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Volkov </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Krikalev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Polyakov </PERSON> are to mothball the Mir and return to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> on April 27. A new crew will be sent up in mid-August to prepare for the attaching the new module, <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said. The attachment contains a space bicycle for cosmonauts, a solar battery to supplement that of the Mir, an East German optical experiment and an airlock through which cosmonauts can pass to take spacewalks. One module, a space laboratory, was attached to Mir in April 1987 and three others are planned, including one to be put up at the end of this year or early next year in which crystals will be grown for semiconductors, electronic parts used in computers and other devices, <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said. One reason for putting Mir on automatic mode is to give a rest to its support staff at mission control and tracking stations that have been working continuously for three years, <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said. `` People are tired. They have n't had vacations. We owe them this,'' he said. Officials have said a ground controller sent an erroneous command to an unmanned Mars probe, Phobos I, in September, leaving it useless. A sister ship, <PERSON> Phobos </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, was lost for still undetermined reasons last month. <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said Mir uses different controllers than those who worked on Phobos, but indicated all are susceptible to fatigue. `` Tiredness can lead to an increase in mistakes, and a break gives a positive effect to a person's work,'' <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said. During the three-month break, he said, scientists will continue to gather data from automatic Mir instruments studying a supernova, photographing the ocean shelf and monitoring meteorites. Engineers are boosting the Mir to a higher orbit to keep its orbit from decaying, <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said. In 1974, the vacant <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Skylab </ORGANIZATION> 4 space station fell into the Earth's atmosphere and disintegrated upon re-entry.
