<HEAD>Court Asked to Rule on High Liability Awards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's second-largest waste hauler is asking the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to reverse a $ 6 million jury verdict against it as an example of `` bloated, irrational and excessive awards'' in liability lawsuits. In a case that businesses say could have an enormous impact on their insurance costs and the overall competitiveness of American industry, <ORGANIZATION> Browning-Ferris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> argued Tuesday against what it called huge punitive damage awards. <ORGANIZATION> BFI </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frey </PERSON> told the high court that enormous punitive damage awards violate the Constitution's Eighth Amendment prohibition against excessive fines, as well as due process rights and common law. The case centers on a lawsuit brought by <ORGANIZATION> Kelco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disposal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, againt Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> BFI </ORGANIZATION>, accusing the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> company of predatory pricing to drive <ORGANIZATION> Kelco </ORGANIZATION> out of business. A <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> jury awarded <ORGANIZATION> Kelco </ORGANIZATION> $ 51,146 in compensatory damages, in contrast to the much larger punitive total. <ORGANIZATION> Kelco </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartow </PERSON> <PERSON> Farr </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> argued the Eighth Amendment's prohibition against excessive fines does not apply to punitive damages `` awarded in a private state court tort action,'' and applying it would be `` intrusive second-guessing'' of jury verdicts <PERSON> Farr </PERSON> said state laws provide for punitive-damage awards to be reviewed by the courts, and such awards are `` routinely reduced.'' `` The courts below upheld this award under traditional common law standards,'' <PERSON> Farr </PERSON> said. `` Damages are simply not fines.'' Dozens of `` friend-of-the-court'' briefs were filed as manufacturers, publishers, insurers, broadcasters, pharmacists, the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, defense attorneys and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> officials all urged the justices to place some limits on punitive damages. They say unfettered jury decisions allowing huge penalty awards are driving up insurance rates and discouraging the marketing of products from medical equipment to football helmets. Trial attorneys and consumer groups, who argue punitive damages are the best protection against bad business practices, have sided with <ORGANIZATION> Kelco </ORGANIZATION>, which survived <ORGANIZATION> BFI </ORGANIZATION>'s price cutting and in 1985 forced the larger company out of town. Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> questioned whether ruling for <ORGANIZATION> BFI </ORGANIZATION> would force the court to review all future punitive-damage awards that someone considered excessive. <PERSON> Frey </PERSON> said that applying the excessive-fines provision in such civil cases would sharply curb a growing trend toward excessive awards that has prompted `` tort reform'' by state legislatures. Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> insisted <PERSON> Frey </PERSON> was seeking a national standard that all 50 states would have to follow, rather than allowing each state to set its own punitive-damage limits. The court is expected to announce its decision by July. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Browning-Ferris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Kelco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disposal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 88-556.
