<HEAD>House Committee Passes $4.7 Billion Measure, Bush Threatens Veto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 1990 budget plan reflecting the deal reached between the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is working its way through the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, but a separate $ 4.7 billion spending bill for this year is ruffling Republican feathers. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> began debating the fiscal 1990 budget resolution on Tuesday and hoped to finish its work today. On Tuesday, it voted 19-4 to reject an amendment by Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, D-La., to institute deep across-the-board spending cuts in place of the compromise reached last week <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, complaining that the bipartisan pact `` does not cut the budget at all,'' said his plan would sent a message `` to start all over again, to do a real job of budgeting.'' Joining <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> was Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., who said, `` If anyone thinks <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Baby </PERSON> was ugly, I suggest taking a close look at this newly hatched baby. Administration officials and congressional leaders ended a month of negotiations last Friday by announcing a deal for $ 1.2 trillion budget that claims a deficit of $ 99.4 billion. The budget committee is charged with producing a congressional resolution that will guide later spending and tax bills for fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1. Chairman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, D-Tenn., said he would oppose any plan that did not follow the White House pact But trouble was brewing across <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> on a so-called dire emergency spending bill for this year. The <ORGANIZATION> House </O