<SECOND>PM-TV Syndication,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coalition Fights to Keep Syndication Rules Intact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A coalition of television producers, unions and station owners says it will fight any attempt by <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> to re-enter and dominate the lucrative syndicated TV market the networks were forced to leave in 1983. The <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday announced that a 207-member coalition would stand in the way of the networks if they attempt to `` gut'' the so-called financial interest and syndication rule. <ORGANIZATION> MPAA </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON> said the coalition was putting the networks on notice that `` we will not lag or hesitate to defend the rule and hold it in place.'' A 1983 consent decree between the networks and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> forced the networks out of the syndication business. That agreement expires in 1990, and the networks and producers have been negotiating to try to reach a new accord without further government intervention. But the talks have reached an impasse, the Coalition to Preserve the Financial Interest and Syndication Rules said. Independent producers say they owe their very existences to the 1983 decree, under which the networks were allowed to keep the programs they broadcast for four years and then return them to producers for sale to independent TV stations and network affiliates. Hit programs such as `` The Cosby Show'' and `` Miami Vice'' can make many millions of dollars in this syndication market. Unlike before, the networks were barred from holding any financial interest in programs they license from outside producers. But the networks take all advertising revenues from a program's network run The program producers, on the other hand, are paid a licensing fee by the networks _ typically $ 1 million to $ 1.5 million for an hourlong program _ that usually does n't meet the total costs of the production. But the producers can profit enormously in syndication with a hit show. `` The rule is working,'' the coalition said. `` The number of independent TV stations has grown; so has the number and quality of producers creating programming for network and syndicated exhibition. ... Meanwhile, the three major networks remain profitable and dominant.'' An <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON>, said the rules, which first were adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in 1970, have `` had exactly the opposite effect from what was intended.'' He said the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 recommended the rules be repealed because the rules `` had concentrated power in the hands of a small number of studios rather than adding to diversity.'' <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Kriegel </PERSON>, senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said he hoped the addition of independent producers to the studio-network negotiations `` will be good for the talks.'' He said the <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> studios, who are in the present coalition, were trying to consolidate their gains against the networks in numerous areas. `` Half the <ORGANIZATION> MPAA </ORGANIZATION> members are in direct competition with the networks,'' <PERSON> Kriegel </PERSON> said. `` Every leader in that community is now going into our business very aggressively.'' The coalition includes the <ORGANIZATION> MPAA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stations </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Directors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theatrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Screen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Actors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> and the Consumer Federation of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.
