<HEAD>Lawmaker Pushes For Fat and Cholesterol Labeling To Fight Heart Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Moakley </PERSON>, D-Mass., has proposed requiring that food products include easily understood details of fat and cholesterol content to help consumers reduce their chances of heart disease `` You could starve to death in the supermarket just reading the labels,'' complained the 61-year-old lawmaker. Under the measure, the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> would require food manufacturers to list the different types of fat _ saturated, polyunsaturated and monounsaturated _ and their amounts. Federal regulations now require food producers to list only the total fat content. The ninth-term <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> said the current labeling provision `` is particularly disturbing since some fats increase blood cholesterol and other types of fat actually lower one's cholesterol. The bill also would require food manufacturers to specify amounts of dietary cholesterol, which also has been linked to heart disease. There currently is no cholesterol labeling requirement.
