<HEAD>Post-Strike Violence Leaves Two Dead, 138 Arrested, Blackouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A general strike against the military government turned violent as police battled demonstrators in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> and other cities and about 50 bomb attacks blacked out much of the capital. Police said they killed two `` extremists'' and arrested more than 130 demonstrators on Tuesday before calm was restored at midnight. Large areas of the capital and other cities had been left without power for several hours. Demonstrators fought police in downtown <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> during daylight Tuesday and then at night in the slums that ring the city. The strike, called by the nation's largest union to protest the incarceration of two labor leaders, failed to generate support from workers but there were clashes between helmeted riot police and demonstrators in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> and other cities. Police said six officers and a security agent were injured in clashes but they did not report injuries among protesters. Hospitals reported receiving `` numerous'' injuries. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said 138 protesters were arrested nationwide and that police resorted to using tear gas and water cannon to scatter the mostly young demonstrators. At night, demonstrators blocked traffic at intersections in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>'s slums, erecting fire barricades. Local radio stations said unidentified gunmen in speeding cars were seen shooting at demonstrators manning the barricades. In the most serious incident, police said two `` extremists'' were killed in a clash with security forces when they were caught planting a bomb near an electrical tower in northern <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>. The strike was called by the opposition <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s largest labor federation with 300,000 members. The union said the strike was to press for the release of its president, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bustos </PERSON>, and its vice president, <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>. Both leaders have been banished in small provincial towns since September after a court sentenced them to 541 days' internal exile for calling another general strike in 1987. Tuesday's strike, however, seemed to have little effect as most factories and businesses operated near normalcy, although school attendance was notably lower than normal. The government pronounced the strike `` a total failure.'' Labor Minister <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> said, `` There has been no strike in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> today.'' He said around 95 percent of the nation's 4.5 million workers were on the job in spite of a cutback in the public transportation system. Several of the bomb blasts destroyed or damaged power towers, blacking out large areas of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> and several other cities for several hours until power could be restored.
