<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-Fusion     04-19 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Fusion,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers in Italy Report New Approach To Cold Fusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists <PERSON> Umberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Colombo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Scaramuzzi </PERSON> say they achieved nuclear fusion at room temperature using a different technique than the recent cold fusion experiments which prompted their tests. <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alternative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> at Frascati, just outside <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Scaramuzzi </PERSON>, who performed the experiments at the agency, both emphasized that it was too early to say if their process would prove practical for generating energy. Their experiments produced large emissions of neutrons but too little energy to register, the two men reported. A neutron is an uncharged elementary particle of an atom. Emissions of neutrons are evidence of fusion. Fusion produces energy when the cores of two hydrogen atoms fuse. It is the process that powers the sun. Fission is atom-splitting, the method employed by conventional nuclear power plants. The Italians began their experiments after <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON>, a chemistry professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION>, and his British colleague, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southampton </ORGANIZATION>, announced to the world on March 23 that they achieved nuclear fusion at room temperature using common laboratory equipment. Researchers have long sought a way to harness nuclear fusion. Standard experiments have used extremely high temperatures. <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> said their experiment ran for more than 100 hours and produced four times as much energy as it used. Their experiments used electrolysis, in which an electrical current was used to herd hydrogen atoms into metal electrodes, where the atoms were apparently forced to fuse because of proximity. Researcher <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> says he found evidence of only very low energy output in a similar experiment. <PERSON> Scaramuzzi </PERSON> told reporters on Tuesday, `` After <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' experiment, I asked myself, how important is electrolysis? There must be more than one road to fusion.'' The Italian experiments did not use electrical current to trigger the reaction, nor did they use `` heavy water,'' which contains a heavy version of hydrogen called deuterium. <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> reported, `` The experiment is totally different from former ones. We have paved the way for a new road to fusion research. What we do n't know yet is if the energy generated is sufficient to justify practical application.'' <PERSON> Scaramuzzi </PERSON>, 60, said, `` If this experiment were not of such great importance to the public, we would never have announced the discovery at this point. We are still in a very preliminary phase.'' He said that on two occasions they measured high emissions of neutrons after placing a sample of the element titanium and deuterium gas in a special metal tube and subjecting it to various pressures and temperatures. The neutrons appeared in one case after applying high pressure and low temperature, and in another at low pressure and room temperature. <PERSON> Scaramuzzi </PERSON> said the energy output of his experiment at this scale was too low to be registered. <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> meanwhile said Monday that further experiments yielded even more energy than the earlier Pons-Fleischmann efforts and ran more efficiently. He said a controlled fusion reaction was sustained for more than 800 hours in a small flask containing heavy water and a palladium electrode and that recent tests produced roughly eight times the energy consumed. <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> said researchers measured the production of 20 to 30 watts of electricity from the experiment, or about 67 watts per cubic centimeter of electrode, compared to 26 watts per cubic centimeter in the earlier experiments. He reported that more than 60 university and private laboratories partly verified the claims he made last month with <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON>. The official Czechoslovak news agency <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that a team of Czechoslovak physicists led by <PERSON> Pavol </PERSON> <PERSON> Povinc </PERSON> also produced room-temperature fusion through the electrolysis method. The team, from the <ORGANIZATION> Comenius </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s faculty of mathematics in <LOCATION> Bratislava </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Slovakia </LOCATION>, said they achieved fusion on Monday.
</TEXT>
