<HEAD>Dollar Off, Nikkei Hits Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar fell today against the Japanese yen, while the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s key index rose slightly to another record high. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed at 33,363.83, up 42.17 points, or 0.13 percent. The index set its previous high of 33,321.66 points on Tuesday, when it edged up 13.33 points. The dollar closed at 131.88 yen, down 0.22 yen from Tuesday's 132.10-yen finish It opened at 131.38 yen but generally moved up during the day, while ranging from 131.35 yen to 131.95 yen. Traders said the currency's lower opening in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> followed a drop on overseas markets, where discouragement over <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic figures released late Tuesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> led to dollar-selling. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that the nation's consumer price index in March rose 0.5 percent, up from February's 0.4 percent, while the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> housing starts in March fell 5.4 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.397 `` But market players -LRB- in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> -RRB- began buying back the dollar toward the end of the morning session for their position adjustments because they thought they had sold too much ahead of the report,'' said a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. There were not enough dollar-buying incentives to push the dollar above 132 yen, he added. On the stock market, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index started higher following a 41.61-point gain in the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> overnight, said a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` Participants took the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic indicators positively as showing a slowdown in the nation's economy,'' he said. Such a slowdown now would ease fears of inflation, prompt expectations of lower interest rates and encourage stock investment. Lower <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates, however, make the dollar less attractive to foreign investors. The dealer added that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s political uncertainties `` have largely discouraged foreign and institutional investors, who hardly participate these days. Major players are only individuals.'' Today's trading was active, with first section volume estimated at 1.4 billion shares, up from Tuesday's 1.1 billion. Among gainers were steel and chemical issues.
