<FIRST>r a PM-FusionTest     04-19 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Test,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Developments On Cold Fusion Front</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> say their experiments with cold fusion prove the energy generated could not have come from a chemical reaction as some skeptics have suggested. The researchers revealed their findings Tuesday, one of several announcements made around the world related to the discovery of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> chemist <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and British colleague <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON>. _ In <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, Italian scientists said they achieved fusion at room temperature with a different process than the one in the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> experiments, which used electrical currents in `` heavy water'' to trigger the reaction `` We have paved the way for a new road to fusion research,'' said <PERSON> Umberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Colombo </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alternative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>. _ In <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, a team of physicists said they also produced room-temperature fusion _ In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> said he wants to help <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alamos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> scientists duplicate his cold fusion experiments so the lab will collaborate with him on research The apparent discovery of cold fusion was announced March 23 by <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON>, who set off an international debate about whether the process was indeed fusion. <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> said they had achieved fusion using ordinary laboratory equipment at room temperatures. Standard experiments have used extremely high temperatures, making them impractical for large-scale energy production because they use more energy than they produce. Since the announcement, scientists have been trying to duplicate the experiment and its results. If fusion can be created as easily as <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> claim, scientists say, it could be a relatively inexpensive and virtually inexhaustible energy source. The Stanford finding came from a team of seven researchers led by <PERSON> Roert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Huggins </PERSON>, professor of material sciences. Displaying a simple experiment with palladium electrodes in tubes of heavy water and plain water in a plastic picnic basket, <PERSON> Huggins </PERSON> said the energy generated was not the result of any known chemical reaction. <PERSON> Huggins </PERSON> would n't speculate on why the experiment produced a 50 percent energy gain in heavy water, but he acknowledged the most likely cause was some kind of fusion process. `` We're seeing excess heat that's above and beyond any possible chemical reaction,'' he said. `` It means the effect is real and is substantial.'' The energy may result, however, from a different type of fusion than is commonly known, he said. <PERSON> Huggins </PERSON>' team ran five experiments over two weeks, using a tube of deuterium oxide, or heavy water, and a tube of plain water. If the experiments produced the same results, they said, it would indicate the energy was not from fusion. Instead, they found much higher temperatures from the heavy water, which meant the energy was not a chemical reaction because there is no essential chemical difference between the two kinds of water. Last week, two graduate students at the Univeristy of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said they had detected cold fusion in an experiment conducted with heavy water, but they could not get the same results using ordinary water. On Monday, <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> said the apparent cold fusion discovery had been partly verified by more than 60 university and private laboratories, but none has reported observing both the production of neutrons and the high level of heat that he and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> produced. The experiment at <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION> was not designed to measure neutrons. Neutrons are a tell-tale sign of fusion, the process powering the sun, in which tremendous amounts of energy are released when hydrogen atoms fuse. In contrast, conventional nuclear power plants use fission, the splitting of atoms.
</TEXT>
