<HEAD>Court Removes Asthmatic Child From Home of Smoking Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENTON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 3-year-old girl with chronic asthma is living in a foster home because a judge ruled her parents were n't doing enough to keep her away from cigarette smoke <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> County </PERSON> social workers removed the girl from her parent's home last month and she remains in a foster home. The girl's name was not released. `` It's a critical situation,'' Circuit Judge <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON> said during a juvenile court hearing March 17. Wise placed the child under the authority of the social services department. `` It is not something that the social services or the medical people are doing on a whim or caprice. They're afraid she's going to die prematurely and unnecessarily if something is n't done,'' Wise said. Wise said the parents could regain custody of their daughter if they make changes in their lives. He granted them full visitation rights. The child was admitted to a hospital near her home on <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s eastern shore, across the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, at least half a dozen times over the past year or so, and on two occasions was transferred to <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> Once, she was admitted to the intensive care unit for treatment of serious respiratory problems associated with asthma. The child lived with her great-grandmother, her legal custodian from March 1987 to March 1988. <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> authorities had granted custody to the relative while the family was living in that state because the girl's parents could not afford to properly care for her. But in March 1988, <LOCATION> Caroline </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> authorities returned the child to her parents, who had moved to <PERSON> Denton </PERSON>. In January, the child's father lost his job and the family moved in with the great-grandmother. Until recently, the girl's parents and great-grandmother smoked. <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, a physician with <ORGANIZATION> Caroline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, testified that on at least two occasions, the girl was in severe respiratory distress when brought to the hospital. Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said that tobacco, which can bring on an asthma attack, may have been a critical factor. `` My particular concerns about this child include that the family continued to smoke despite many warnings that this was not appropriate,'' Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. `` I do know that they tried to smoke outside the home or at least they were reporting that to us. But because the smoke is carried on clothing and other articles and in the car, this simply is not measure enough.''
