<HEAD>Opposition Leader Freed After 18-Month Detention Without Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Kit Siang comments, details.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The country's leading opposition politician, <PERSON> Lim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kit </PERSON> <PERSON> Siang </PERSON>, was released from prison today after being held without charge for 18 months. With the release of <PERSON> Lim </PERSON> and his son <PERSON> Lim </PERSON> <PERSON> Guan </PERSON> <PERSON> Eng </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Kamunting </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Detention </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION>, 120 miles north of this capital, the Malay-dominated government has freed all 106 people it arrested during an October 1987 crackdown. The government that year angered many ethnic Chinese, who generally maintain their separate culture and language, by assigning non-Chinese speaking teachers to Chinese primary schools. Prime Minister <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohamad </PERSON>, himself a Malay, has said the 1987 arrests of opposition politicians, environmentalists, trade unionists, church workers, educators and others was necessary to prevent Malay-Chinese rioting. But Kit Siang described the last 18 months as `` a nightmare for democratic rights in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>.'' His primary concern now, he said, `` is to do all I can to restore public confidence in democracy and restore <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>'s image abroad.'' Both <PERSON> Kit </PERSON> <PERSON> Siang </PERSON>, who is Secretary-General of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and his son are members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and ethnic Chinese. Fellow <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> members <PERSON> Vethamuthu </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> and <PERSON> Karpal </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> were released a few months ago but were told they could not speak to the press, that they have to report to police if they leave their hometown, are prohibited from addressing public gatherings and must report to the authorities every month. <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> has said that through their actions and speeches those arrested in 1987 had increased racial tension in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, where government policy promotes Malays' economic standing in a country long dominated by Chinese businessmen. Every business in the country must be partially owned by Malays, who also are given tax breaks for starting their own companies. Universities teach in Malay, which has been named the national language, and <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION> has been named the state religion. The country's 17 million population is 55 percent Malay and 37 percent Chinese, with most of the remainder Indian. The races in this former British colony have argued periodically over language, cultural and other differences, but there has been no major unrest since 500 people died in Malay-Chinese rioting in 1969. When <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> became prime minister in July 1981, 550 people were being held under the Internal Security Act, which allows imprisonment without trial. <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> called for a review and released most of them. Deputy Home Affairs Minister <PERSON> Megat </PERSON> <PERSON> Junid </PERSON> <PERSON> Megat </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayub </PERSON> says 70 people are still held without trial under the act. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lam </PERSON> <PERSON> Thye </PERSON>, also an ethnic Chinese and a member of parliament who has been the acting leader of the opposition and secretary general in <ORGANIZATION> Kit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Siang </ORGANIZATION>'s absence, called on the government `` to release all the other internal security act detainees or charge them in an open court of law.''
