<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-BirdRehab 1stLd-Writethru a0450 04-19 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Bird Rehab, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0450,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Center Works To Save Oiled Birds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS to Cullowhee sted Collowhee in 3rd graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While the effort to clean oil-drenched beaches sputters to life, volunteers armed with dish soap are wearily trying to save birds marked for death by sticky goo from the Exxon Valdez. Outside a makeshift rehabilitation center in a college dormitory, already cleaned cormorants gingerly spread their wings to dry in the sun. Ducks bob in plywood-sided tanks. The smell of fish used as food permeates the air. `` The ones that make it this far, into those tanks, usually make it,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Masson </PERSON>, a volunteer from <LOCATION> Cullowhee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> `` If they're in there they'll probably be OK.'' Many do not survive after reaching the center, run by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bird </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a California-based non-profit corporation The center's executive director, <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkner </PERSON>, said 349 oil-coated birds have been brought in since the tanker rammed <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> on March 24, spilling more than 10 million gallons of North Slope crude into Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. Of the 349, 136 died from the oil's toxic effects, exposure, dehydration or loss of bouyancy. Twenty-two have been returned to the wild. Many are being held at the center because they might return to the oil-contaminated areas. By Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> had logged 1,850 birds found dead in the sound since the spill. But the true number of dead birds and animals will never be known because of the sound's vast distances and remote shorelines. Ms. <PERSON> Berkner </PERSON> said as the oil has spread, the effort to save birds has widened. She said the organization has opened a cleaning center in <LOCATION> Seward </LOCATION> and she was going to <LOCATION> Kodiak </LOCATION> to open another. Luckily, there were few ducks and shorebirds in the sound when the tanker hit the rocks. It was before the spring arrival of waterfowl. Ms. <PERSON> Berkner </PERSON> was unsure how birds migrating into the sound now might be affected. `` I think right now, let's wait and see,'' she said. `` We're hoping the slick will break up ... We're preparing for the worst and hoping for the best.'' For Ms. <PERSON> Berkner </PERSON>, this spill is not the first. Her first was in 1971, after two <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> tankers collided in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. `` I just went down and helped for two weeks. That two weeks turned into 18 years,'' she said. In Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, the birds are picked up in the sound by 43 boats under contract to <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>. The vessels also pick up dead birds for disposal. Once aboard the vessels, the birds are kept warm and given liquids. Each night, the day's haul is transferred to the cleanup center. In <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, the birds are checked for injuries, banded and held for washing. The workers use a popular dishwashing liquid. Inside the center, activity seems constant as seven paid staff members and the 20 or so volunteers rush to clean birds. Carpeted floors are covered with plastic. Notes are taped to walls. In the `` dirty bird'' room, candidates for cleaning wait in plywood enclosures with coarse wire floors. The boxes are covered with sheets to give the birds privacy. `` It takes two to 12 tubs of water to clean the birds,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, coordinator for the volunteers. Just rinsing the birds can take 45 minutes, she said. In the `` clean bird'' room, the birds are held in covered enclosures warmed by commercial pet dryers. Then they are observed in the tanks outside to ensure they can float and will not succumb to hypothermia. The tanks are an attraction for visitors and workers. `` This is what makes it worthwhile _ coming out here and watching the silly birds eating and splashing around,'' Ms. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
