<HEAD>Soldiers Wound 17 in Gaza</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers shot and wounded at least 17 Palestinians in clashes today, including 11 children who suffered mostly head injuries from rubber and plastic bullets, Arab hospital officials said. Today's violence occurred as soldiers and police beefed up security in the occupied lands and inside <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to prevent riots or attacks on Jews during the seven-day Jewish Passover holiday, which begins tonight. A public opinion survey published by a newspaper indicated 65 percent of Israelis supported a peace plan by Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> that calls for Arabs in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> to elect representatives for peace talks. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hamishmar </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said that Jewish settlers in the occupied lands have formed a committee seeking to stop the election plan, which they claim would `` bring about a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state.'' In the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, soldiers clashed with stone-throwing youths today in the <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yunis </PERSON> and Nusseirat refugee camps, the village of <LOCATION> Beit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hanoun </LOCATION> and a neighborhood in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Arab hospital officials said the wounded included six chidren age 14 or younger who were hit with rubber bullets in the head and face. Five other youths were struck with plastic or rubber bullets in other parts of the body. The officials said six people ages 17 to 30 also were injured with plastic bullets. In Arab east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, police detained 27 Palestinians accused of involvement in stone-throwing riots after midnight, in which three policemen and two Arabs were injured, said the <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> police spokesman, <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandori </PERSON>. In the 16-month uprising, 439 Palestinians have been killed, most shot by soldiers quelling stone-throwing protests. Eighteen Israelis also have died. The <ORGANIZATION> Yediot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ahronot </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said it conducted the public opinion survey on <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s plan April 12-16 in face-to-face interviews with a random sample of 656 Israelis. Sixty-five percent said they supported the elections plan and 31 percent were opposed, while 4 percent said they had no view, the newspaper said. No margin of error was given for the poll. A Western relief official in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> said that about 40 percent of the wounded in the Palestinian revolt are now 15 and younger. `` In the beginning of the uprising, the average age of those getting shot was much higher,'' said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
