<HEAD>Couple Convicted For Failing To Treat Ill Daughter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to restore time element</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Christian Science couple was found guilty of murder for allowing their 7-year-old diabetic daughter to die without medical attention because of their religious beliefs. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hermanson </PERSON>, 42, and his wife, <PERSON> Christine </PERSON>, 38, could be sentenced to three to seven years in prison under state sentencing guidelines. They were allowed to remain free until sentencing. No sentencing date has been set. A jury found the Hermansons guilty Tuesday of third-degree murder and child abuse in the 1986 death of their daughter, <PERSON> Amy </PERSON>. They had rejected a plea bargain agreement for 15 years' probation in exchange for a plea of guilty or no contest. `` We will be filing motions for a new trial,'' said defense attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>. He said he was `` disappointed and surprised'' at the verdict. The Hermansons were the first Christian Scientists in 20 years prosecuted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for denying a child medical care for religious reasons, church representatives said. Five other religious exemption cases are pending, three in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, one each in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. The defense said the case was about religious freedom and cited a 1975 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law that protects parents who withhold medical treatment from their sick children if they are `` legitimately practicing'' their religious beliefs. Prosecutors contended it was murder, saying the girl died after her parents ignored pleas to take her to a doctor and relied instead on prayer to heal her untreated diabetes. Christian Scientists rely on prayer instead of medicine to care for the ill and may call on church-accredited `` practitioners'' with expertise in spiritual healing. However, members may seek medical assistance without fear of sanctions. <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Talbot </PERSON>, church spokesman from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, said the conviction would tend to unify Christian Scientists. The church must `` do a fuller job of helping society understand that it has a wonderful gift in spiritual healing and it would be a loss for all of us to prosecute out of existence spiritual healing,'' he said. But <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Swan </PERSON>, a former Christian Scientist from <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> who began a campaign to fight religious exemption laws after losing a son to meningitis 12 years ago, called the verdict significant. `` It signals to the nation that society does not approve of this behavior, and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientists </ORGANIZATION> had better wake up and listen,'' she said. `` These jurors could not accept the notion that a child should be allowed to die of diabetes for which, everybody knows, there is a standard, very effective treatment.'' Last week, with the jury out of the room, a witness testified that both parents had sought medical treatment for themselves but not for their daughter. The jury never heard that testimony because the judge ruled that prosecutors had improperly withheld the information from defense attorneys.
