<HEAD>NATO Defense Ministers Gather For Nuclear Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from Cheney. Pickup
7th pvs, ``Bush and...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Defense Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> defense ministers today began talks likely to center on the politically sensitive issue of upgrading short-range nuclear missiles in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON>, attending his first gathering of the 16-nation <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, was expected to press the allies for a new _ and stronger _ commitment to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plans to modernize the weapons. `` I think it is important that we go forward to modernize that force,'' he told reporters aboard his <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> jet en route <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. He reiterated American opposition to <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> negotiations on reducing short-range weapons in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` Now is the time, I believe, to move forward on conventional -LRB- non-nuclear -RRB- forces,'' he said. <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and some other <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> nations want <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> to indicate its willingness to open talks on short-range nuclear weapons with the Soviet-led <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>. Officials said it was unlikely the defense ministers would discuss the matter in any depth at this two-day meeting. There appears to be a desire on the part of the allies, officials said, to show cohesion in advance of a May summit between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> leaders. The ministers also were not scheduled to make any key decisions on modernization, which is strongly opposed in some European countries. But they will be asked to reaffirm their backing to plans to upgrade the current Lance surface-to-surface missile. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> contends it needs a strong signal from the allies to lobby <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for money to continue a research-and-development program for the weapon. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> leaders will meet at the end of May and discuss the modernization plans as part of a blueprint designed to guide the alliance in arms control and force planning in the coming years. The modernization issue has become increasingly sensitive in recent months. Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has said he wants to delay a decision on deployment of the new missile until 1991 or 1992 _ after elections in his country. <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> recently added to the uncertainty by saying it, too, wanted decisions put off until the early 1990s. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat said decisions on producing and deploying the missile were not expected for several more years. The Lance missile, introduced in 1972, will become obsolete in 1995. The missile has a range of 60 miles and its replacement would be extended to more than 250 miles, just under the limits of the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty. The accord eliminates <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet land-based missiles with ranges of about 300 to 3,400 miles. There are currently 88 Lance launchers, most of them in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON>, commander of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s European forces, argued for modernizing the short-range missile force in an article Tuesday in the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>. He said the Soviet-led <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGAN