<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Paramount Pictures and a movie theater ca n't be held responsible for the death of a teen-ager stabbed by a young man who had just seen a 1979 film about city gangs, the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has ruled. The victim's family sued <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Saxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, seeking damages on the grounds of wrongful death. It charged that Paramount and the theater knew `` The Warriors'' was inciting violence around the country. Three days before the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> slaying, according to court records, two other youths were killed near theaters showing the film in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oxnard </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. That same week, Paramount officers advised theaters showing the film to hire security guards and offered to pay for them The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> high court upheld the dismissal of the family's lawsuit by a lower court on the ground that the movie-maker and theater company had no `` special relationship'' to the dead youth and therefore had no duty to protect him from his attacker. In addition, the court rejected the family's contention that `` The Warriors'' was an incitement to violence. `` Although the film is rife with violent scenes, it does not at any point exhort, urge, entreat, solicit or overtly advocate or encourage unlawful or violent activity on the part of viewers,'' Justice <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> wrote. `` It does not create the likelihood of inciting or producing ` imminent lawless action' that would strip the film of First Amendment protection.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Yakubowicz </PERSON> filed the lawsuit in 1981 on behalf of his dead son, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, 16. The youth was stabbed Feb. 15, 1979, at a subway station several miles from the theater by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON>, who was returning from seeing `` The Warriors'' at the Saxon Theater. <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON>, who sat through two showings of the movie, taunted Yakubowicz on the subway, imitating a line from the movie _ `` I want you, I'm going to get you.''
