<HEAD>Bureaucracy, Slow Donations Hamper Sudan Relief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to ADD attack on convoy. Pickup 6th graf
pvs, ``U.N. organizers...'' TRIMS thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bureaucracy, slow donor support, bad planning and the civil war have forced organizers to scale down a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> relief effort to save millions of people in the south from starvation or malnutrition. Attackers on Tuesday ambushed the first convoy bringing supplies to rebel-held southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, destroying the lead vehicle and killing eight rebel escorts, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, reported today. Even before the ambush, organizers said Operation Lifeline-Sudan now expects to provide less than half the 100,000 tons of relief goods believed to be necessary if a second consecutive summer disaster is to be avoided. When the relief effort began April 1, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> planned to stockpile supplies at strategic points in southern and southwestern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> for people escaping famine caused by the 6-year-long civil war in the region. Relief goods must be in place before the summer rains turn much of the rural south into lakes and isolate areas where the refugees gather. Almost three weeks after the starting date, no deliveries have been made by trains or <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> barge convoys, the project's bulk carriers. Airlifts have been delayed because planes promised by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other Western donors have not arrived. <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Weathers </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, said the 14-truck convoy to the town of <LOCATION> Torit </LOCATION> was attacked Tuesday afternoon 14 miles west of a rebel base at <LOCATION> Kapoeta </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION> did not say who they believe was responsible for the ambush, but they said it was unlikely rebels were responsible because of the rebel escort. The officials said that overland route would be suspended but other relief operations would move forward. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> organizers have given up their original goal of completing the $ 132 million operation by the end of April and say it will continue as long as allowed by the rains, which normally begin in May. Food has been stored in some areas of the three southern regions, but supplies in other towns are precariously low and the possibility of replenishing them appears slim. Project director <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wannop </PERSON>, local head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Development Program, insisted `` there are signs of momentum gathering'' and expressed hope that half the 100,000 tons of food and medicine would be within reach of 2.3 million southerners by the end of April. Only about 26,000 tons are in the stockpiles now, he said. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials say 100,000 face starvation without emergency supplies. Relief agencies estimated 250,000-500 ,000 southerners died in 1988 from the war and the famine it created To attract international attention, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Children's Fund flew in actress <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Hepburn </PERSON>, its goodwill ambassador, and some of the bad planning became evident. In <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, she was driven around aimlessly for an hour by escorts who had not been told her schedule. Operation Lifeline-Sudan sometimes appears to face an endless list of problems. After promising two military C-130 transport for the airlift, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> backed out because <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officers thought the planes might be exposed to hostile fire. The <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> office of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> said it would charter two of the cargo jets but there is no indication when that will be done. Shortages of fuel have grounded available planes and disabled trucks. Bureaucracy contributes to the bottlenecks with such policies as requiring relief workers to obtain travel permits. Customs problems continue despite Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>'s promises at the March conference to eliminate them <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s cumbersome bureaucratic pace was slowed even more by the advent April 7 of <LOCATION> Ramadan </LOCATION>, the holy month when Moslems abstain from food and drink in daylight hours. <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> and the rest of northern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> are Arab and predominantly Moslem. The civil war grew out of demands by black southerners, most of whom are Christians or animists, for autonomy and a better economic deal. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, regional director of <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> for the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, said: `` There have been lots of disappointments: that the donor community has been slow in responding, that the military actions have not diminished, disappointments with the logistical and mechanical obstacles.''
