<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two crewmen missing since their freighter sank Monday morning might still be alive because the area they are believed to be drifting in is warmed by the Gulf Stream, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials said today. Twenty-three sailors were rescued after the Star of <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION> sank in story seas about 400 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> cutter was to continue searching for the two men at least through the day, said Petty Officer <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawley </PERSON>. On Tuesday, a search plane reported spotting one missing crewman, but it was not clear whether he was alive. <PERSON> Crawley </PERSON> said rescuers have not found any further sign of him. `` We feel they're still out there or else we would n't be searching,'' said Chief Petty Officer <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> headquarters. <PERSON> Crawley </PERSON> said officials believe the men may still be alive because of warm currents. One of the men was wearing a life jacket when he was swept out of a life raft, survivors said. They said the other man may have injured himself jumping from the ship. It was unclear what caused the ship to sink, said Petty Officer <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Rives </PERSON>. The Ravenscraig, a freighter, picked up the 23 multinational crew members Monday after rescue planes spotted a lifeboat and a life raft and guided the 950-foot vessel to them, <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> said. An empty life raft also was recovered. The men suffered only minor injuries. The 500-foot Star of <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION> was bound for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, when crew members reported about 9 a.m. that it began taking on water in 12-foot seas and winds of 30-35 mph, <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> said.
