<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leader of the team that redesigned faulty space shuttle booster rockets is leaving the space agency to join an aerospace firm. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, special assistant to the director of the <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, will become site director for <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> at the Kennedy Space Center. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, 52, has worked for the <ORGANIZATION> Natinal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> for 28 years. He helped pinpoint a failed booster rocket seal as the cause of the January 28, 1986, explosion that killed the seven-member crew of Challenger. In May 1986, he was named manager of the program that redesigned the boosters. The solid fuel rockets, with new joint seals, have since flown successfully three times.
