<HEAD>Police Say Drunkenness Factor In Disaster; Coverup Charged</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with report of earlier arrests
for drunkeness. Pickup 5th, `To relieve...'' Inserts 2 grafs after 10th,
``None of...' with reax of Soviet player. Pickup 11th, `News reports...''
TRIMS.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A councilman in <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> said today that police, who have largely blamed the weekend's soccer disaster on hooliganism and drunkeness, are trying to cover up their own incompetence. The charge came while police and government officials launched inquiries to determine how a surging crowd was allowed to crush and suffocate people at the soccer match, leaving 95 dead. The Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today quoted police officials as saying they were disgusted by reports portraying Saturday's disaster at <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> stadium in <LOCATION> Sheffield </LOCATION> as a consequence of their failure to control the crowd. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Middup </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yorkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, the local police union chapter, claimed drunkenness contributed to the uncontrolled crush of <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION> fans outside the stadium just as the match between <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Nottingham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> was beginning. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yorkshire </LOCATION> police said today that some fans were arrested before the game for public order offenses but refused to give any details. To relieve the dangerous crush outside the stadium, police ordered that a locked gate be opened. The fans poured into a standing-room `` terrace'' area already crowded with other <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> fans, and victims were trampled or crushed to death against a 10-foot-high steel-mesh fence. `` We are quite convinced that a lot of the fans _ many, many hundreds of them outside that gate _ had been drinking very heavily,'' he said on <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> television. Given the behavior police faced outside the stadium, <PERSON> Middup </PERSON> said, `` I do n't know what we are supposed to do and why it should all be our fault.'' He also said officers saw people picking up victims' belongings. The Times said other police officers reported seeing <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> fans picking the pockets of the dead. <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Keva </PERSON> <PERSON> Coombe </PERSON> called the police allegations `` baseless, malicious and wicked'' and said they `` are contradicted by the observations of thousands of people who were present, from all sections of society.'' `` None of these allegations were made at the time and any lawyer will know that they have the hallmarks of an attempt to create a cover story to cover for their incompetence,'' he said. In another development today, Soviet soccer star <PERSON> Oleg </PERSON> <PERSON> Blokhin </PERSON>, who plays for an Austrian team, condemned the `` deplorable conditions'' of the <LOCATION> Sheffield </LOCATION> stadium, the official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` I believe it is an outright crime to pack spectators into standing sectors like sardines in a can,'' <PERSON> Blokhin </PERSON> was quoted as saying. The disaster has focused attention on <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s antiquated soccer stadiums and the riot fences located in standing-room-only areas near the soccer goals. News reports have centered on speculation the deaths may have been caused by the decision of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yorkshire </LOCATION> police Supt. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> to order the gate unlocked. Nine survivors of Saturday's disaster are suing <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yorkshire </LOCATION> police and the owners of the stadium, alleging negligence. Police officials quoted by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> expressed disgust at the behavior of <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION> fans as officers attended to the victims. The paper quoted one unnamed senior police officer as saying: `` As we struggled in appalling conditions to save lives, fans standing further up ... were openly urinating on us and the bodies of the dead. `` As policemen on the pitch tried to save the injured, they were hampered by other <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> fans running up, kicking and punching them,'' the officer said. On Tuesday, a senior judge, Sir <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, began a government-ordered inquiry into the disaster by touring the stadium. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said it was too early to pinpoint major issues of the inquiry but said he would look at the effect of liquor on the fans' behavior The death toll rose Tuesday to 95 with the death of a hospitalized 14-year-old boy. Nineteen injured fans remained hospitalized today, nine in intensive care, hospital officials said. British soccer fans have a reputation for violence _ rioting <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> fans are blamed for <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>'s 1985 <LOCATION> Heysel </LOCATION> stadium disaster when 39 mostly Italian fans died. As a result, rival fans have been segregated and fenced in at <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> and other British grounds to keep them from fighting and running onto the field.
