<FIRST>r a PM-TrainingTeachers     04-19 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Training Teachers,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Finds Continuing Shortfall Of Science And Math Teachers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nationwide shortage of math and science instructors probably will continue into the next century, but alternative teacher training programs help offset the shortfall, a study has found. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will need about 20,000 new math and science teachers each year for the next decade, says <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Darling-Hammond </PERSON>, lead author of a <ORGANIZATION> Rand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> study on teacher education, which was released Tuesday. The study found that postgraduate training programs for career switchers, retirees and other non-traditional teacher recruits produce about 2,000 science and math instructors a year, or 10 percent of the shortfall. Less than half of the demand will be met by graduates of traditional education programs by 1992, the study adds. Ms. <PERSON> Darling-Hammond </PERSON> noted that the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> estimates that about 30 percent of the people teaching math or science are not fully prepared. `` Quite often a physical education teacher will be asked to teach biology because some administrators view the curriculum requirements as similar,'' she said. This produces recurring problems with poor student achievement in the sciences and math, she said. `` Our very best math students, the top 5 percent of our students, score below the average for students in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' Ms. <PERSON> Darling-Hammond </PERSON> said. `` If we do n't improve our ability to produce large numbers of well-trained people in scientific and technical fields, we will not be able to compete economically in the international marketplace,'' Ms. <PERSON> Darling-Hammond </PERSON> said. The biggest obstacles reported in recruiting and retaining good science and math teachers are similar to those for teachers in general: relatively low pay, student disciplinary problems, poor student motivation, excessive paperwork and assignment to non-teaching chores. The Rand study, `` Redesigning Teacher Education: Opening the Door for New Recruits to Science and Mathematics Training,'' generally found that there are two ways to increase the supply of entrants to an occupation. `` Increase the benefits or attractions to the field or reduce the costs of entry. Efforts to improve teacher salaries and working conditions are intended to address the first of these ... -LRB- and -RRB- non-traditional programs attend to the second of these strategies: They aim to lower the financial and opportunity costs of preparing to teach.'' Non-traditional programs focus on training people who did not consider math or science teaching while they were in college. But a Rand survey of 64 such programs, comprising most of the programs nationwide, found significant differences. In some cases, programs have been closed for lack of funding since the survey was done two years ago. The extent of study required varied from as few as 16 weeks to two years or more, requiring completion of as few as nine course credits to as many as 45. Some provide student teaching experience, but not all.
</TEXT>
