<SECOND>PM-Iran-Iraq,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Arrives In Geneva For New Round Of Iran-Iraq Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> arrived today to oversee a new round of peace talks between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, but negotiators for both sides said they are not prepared to compromise. At an airport press conference, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> acknowledged that the adversaries are `` are still rather far apart'' but said it is important to keep the eight-month process going. The two countries have been trying to work out a permanent peace accord since they signed a cease-fire in August, ending eight years of war that killed or injured at least 1 million people. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> declined to predict the outcome of the new negotiations. However, he said the mere fact that the foreign ministers of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> agreed to come to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> showed their interest in reaching an agreement. Before leaving <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> early today, Iranian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would not yield in its demand that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> first withdraw its troops from Iranian territory. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> claims that Iraqi forces still hold 1,065 square miles of Iranian territory. By <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> estimates, however, only about 260 square miles remain under Iraqi control. On Tuesday, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> accused <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of sabotaging the talks by `` procrastination, maneuvering and insincerity'' and warned that the negotiations `` could eventually collapse.'' He was due in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> today. The talks 