<TEXT>
 April 12 <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- S.D. -RRB- American News on the minimum wage: When we first considered the minimum wage issue, we thought it was obvious that the wage should be raised. After reading articles from several sources, however, we discovered there is no easy answer. ... An <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> survey found that 90 percent of its members agree that a minimum wage increase results in more unemployment among young and unskilled workers. These jobs will be lost because employers will decide to have fewer employees since their wages will be higher. ... The worst part of this situation is that those the higher wage is intended to help _ those with the fewest job skills _ will be the first to be unemployed. ... It is impossible to tell those earning minimum wage that they are making enough money, but the decision may easily turn into a choice between a low-paying job or no job. Either way, no one wins.
