 April 12 The News-Review, <LOCATION> Roseburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, on housing policies: There is ample evidence that Secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> is fostering a new and important spirit of cooperation with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. ... For instance, ... <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> has expressed great interest in a comprehensive housing bill introduced in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> earlier this month with broad bipartisan support. ... <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s new policies emphasize the importance of helping low-income families to work actively toward solving their own housing problems, rather than being the passive recipients of federal largesse. Part of -LRB- <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s -RRB- master plan is the creation of federal enterprise zones to attract businesses to poverty-stricken inner cities and rural areas. ... Another important part of the overall housing plan is the concept of urban homesteading, which enables people living in public housing to buy their own homes. ... <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> is now working on a plan to provide temporary accommodation for the homeless in unused federal buildings throughout the nation. ... These common-sense policies bring self-respect, dignity, and above all, hope, to a section of the population which too often finds itself trapped in a cycle of despair and poverty.
