<HEAD>UNDATED: larger culprits.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 April 17 The <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> on the British soccer tragedy: A soccer match, a time for recreation and merriment, instead turned into a maelstrom, as nearly 100 persons were killed in the crush of spectators at a match Saturday in <LOCATION> Sheffield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. The episode teaches important lessons about both the importance and danger of sports, and it demonstrates the need for measures to prevent a recurrence. It occurred as fans surged forward in overcrowded stands. The victims were crushed and suffocated in a `` terrace,'' or standing-room-only pen, at the end of the stadium. Thousands of eager, excited fans had gathered at the stadium hoping to watch the game. ... For too many Britons, sports is also something to fight about. English soccer clubs were banned from <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> tournaments in 1985 after 39 people were killed in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> when backers of a British team rioted during a match with an Italian team. If <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sports has been marred by drugs -LRB- and, now, possibly, gambling -RRB-, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> soccer has been marred by violence. While hooliganism in the stands has been an occasional problem during football, baseball and other games in this country, crowd control is taken seriously by most big-time sports executives here, as it should be. It obviously needs to be taken more seriously in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 April 18 <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION> -RRB- Capital-Journal on the British soccer tragedy: The carnage is senseless, and the immediate reaction to such devastation is to seek out someone to blame. The finger has been pointed first at the guards who opened the gates to the fans. Certainly hindsight raises questions about their decision, although there is evidence that the decision was made out of fear of a similar crunch at the turnstiles. <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> has demonstrated the ugly consequences when crowds get out of hand. The lesson should serve as a reminder that patience is important in wait-your-turn situations. It also should make officials involved in such operations re-examine the way crowds are handled and accommodated. It may save lives.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 April 17 The Morning News Tribune, <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, on <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> procurement: The conviction ... of two <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> executives for their roles in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> procurement scandal sends a clear, strong signal to other corporation officials: They will be held accountable when they know about wrongdoing and allow it to continue. The executives, found guilty of conspiracy and wire fraud, face long prison sentences _ up to 40 years _ and large fines. Prosecutors argued that the two were aware a consultant was paying a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> procurement official for inside information that led to <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> landing a $ 24 million contract. The significance of the conviction, according to assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Aronica </PERSON>, is that it tells executives `` they can not put things into motion and feign ignorance and attempt to wash their hands of guilt.'' Although the company itself already has agreed to pay $ 4.3 million in penalties, this kind of corruption can best be addressed by holding the top people personally accountable. Shareholders end up footing the bill for fines; prison time, however, is a real attention-getter.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 April 17 <LOCATION> Hattiesburg </LOCATION> -LRB- Miss. -RRB- American on school drinking water: A report on the safety of school drinking water released last week by the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> gives every one of us reason for concern. Federal studies suggest that water from at least 10 percent of faucets in each school contains high lead levels; 20 parts per billion poses a health risk. What's more, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said at least 1 million lead-contaminated drinking fountains may be operating in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> schools _ some with up to 400 times the amount of lead considered safe by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>. The culprits are old and new plumbing and drinking fountains that are lead-lined or have lead solder. The danger is particularly great in fountains or faucets that are used intermittenly and thus allow the water to stand in the pipes, as in the case in schools. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> is recommending that at least some of the fountains in every school in the nation be tested. ... This is a potentially serious problem, but it is a problem that can be dealt with. The answer lies in testing those fountains now and taking quick action to remove any that reveal dangerous levels of lead.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 April 14 <LOCATION> Owatonna </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on smokers suing tobacco companies: Smokers who die from lung cancer and their survivors may sue tobacco companies, the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has ruled. ... That is not to say these suits have particular merit, however, or that the plaintiffs should be awarded any damages. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Forster </PERSON>, 46, died of lung cancer in 1985, but not before suing <ORGANIZATION> R.J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for causing his cancer. The truth of the matter is that <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Forster </PERSON> had 25 years of warnings before he finally died of cancer. ... <PERSON> R.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> took certain actions that may have led to his death, it's true. But so did <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Forster </PERSON>. There is an element of personal responsibility here. Perhaps it was not his fault that he became addicted. To be sure, it is not his widow's fault. We would not deny him or his family human compassion. But we can not use lawsuits to vent our frustrations or anger at the hand we are dealt in life, or the hand we draw. We make mistakes, and we live with them _ and sometimes, sadly, we die with them.
