<HEAD>Volcker Pushes Congressional, Executive Pay Boost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of a private commission that recommended federal pay increases said Wednesday they are glad President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has proposed a raise for judges but disappointed he did not also call for more money for members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and top government officials. `` We were disappointed by what he decided to do right now,'' political scientist <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> at a hearing on recommendations of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is quite clear the president does n't want to grapple with the situation in the aftermath of what happened in January and February,'' <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> said. `` He is trying to find ways simply not to look at the mess right now.'' Before leaving office in January, former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> approved a government commission's recommendation calling for a 50 percent increases for judges, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and high federal officials. The proposal aroused a storm of public criticism and was rejected by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in February. The private commission also recommended raises for all three branches of government in a report submitted to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on March 29. The president, however, proposed a 25 percent hike for judges only, in an ethics proposal he unveiled April 12. He put off the question of other increases. Former <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, now chairman of the private commission, said, `` We welcome the president's initiative in respect to raising the pay of federal judges We believe, however, that increases are essential for the other branches as well.'' `` Pay for the public servants of government must rank substantially higher in the range of government's budget priorities,'' <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> told the committee. <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> said that on the basis of the commission's meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> when they submitted their report he believed that `` before long he will want to work out something that will cut across all branches.'' Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, D-Mich., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee, said, `` While much debate has focused on the role which compensation plays in the government's ability to recruit and retain, the recommendations of the commission are much broader in scope than a single plug for a pay raise for executives, judges or anyone else. <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> told the committee that `` it would be a misreading of our intention and conclusions to place undue emphasis on one area _ such as pay _ to the exclusion of others.'' One of the most important things, he said, is a recommendation that Cabinet officers and agency heads be given `` greater flexibility to administer their organizations. ... In short, we urge greater delegation of personnel authority and easier procedures for hiring and firing.'' The commission also called for `` a partial, but decisive, reversal of the trend extending over many years for an increased number of political appointees _ now standing at over 3,000'' in the executive branch.
</TEXT>
