<HEAD>Media Stumble Through Presentation of Notorious Centennial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 West German media have stumbled through an awkward observance of <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s birth 100 years ago, reflecting a hesitance among many to come to grips with the once-revered Fuehrer. The unsavory anniversary has been noted in a disjointed series of newspaper portraits, historical analyses and opinion polls that explain only pieces of the phenomenon that brought death for millions during World War II and the Holocaust, and the enduring division of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. One radio network in <LOCATION> Hesse </LOCATION> state planned a discussion of residual right-wing extremist tendencies for Thursday's anniversary of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s birth in the Austrian village of <LOCATION> Braunau </LOCATION>, on <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s southern border. But other media seemed more poised to react to expected demonstrations by the neo-Nazi fringe than to put the occasion into perspective for a nation still branded by crimes committed before many people were born. The <ORGANIZATION> ZDF </ORGANIZATION> television network announced two months ago it would not have any documentaries on the anniversary, which it said was `` not the right day to remember a criminal.'' Newspapers and magazines across the entire political spectrum have made virtually no mention of plans by neo-Nazi leaders like <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuehnen </PERSON> to celebrate <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s centennial. Federal officials in the capital have been careful to avoid discussion of the infamous occasion. <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael-Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Butz </PERSON> was asked what steps federal forces have taken to ensure the safety of potential targets of neo-Nazi actions. `` We have taken adequate precautions where needed,'' he replied, declining to elaborate. Among the press reviews of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s role in German history, the most comprehensive and critical analysis has been offered by <ORGANIZATION> Der </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spiegel </ORGANIZATION> magazine. The glossy weekly devoted its April 10 cover and 20 pages to try to explain `` The terrorist of the century'' and how he has affected today's <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> published in detail the results of a nationwide opinion poll conducted in March by the respected <ORGANIZATION> Emnid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bielefeld </ORGANIZATION>. Responses by the 2,200 West Germans polled indicated widespread uncertainty about how to assess <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>, as well as some worrisome indications of latent anti-Semitism and positive views toward the dictator. An astounding 38 percent of those polled replied `` yes'' to the question: `` If not for the war and the Holocaust, would <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> have been a great German statesman?'' The poll also revealed that 46 percent of the respondents, said by the <ORGANIZATION> Emnid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> to represent accurately West German voters, consider the Third Reich to have had some positive influences. Asked to evaluate their attitude toward Jews in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, 18 percent described their views as negative and 33 percent chose zero on the scale that ranged from minus 5 for very negative attitudes to plus 5 for very positive. The complex bundle of nationalist feelings carried by many West Germans was illustrated by reaction to the statement `` I am proud to be a German,'' to which only 27 percent of the respondents fully agreed. The poll also suggested that most West Germans believe the division of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is permanent, and that more than two thirds of the respondents would like to be done with `` the past.'' Quick, a weekly picture magazine, also carried a photo essay on <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> and his legacy, with similar poll results indicating strong pockets of right-wing extremism in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and substantial numbers of citizens _ 18 percent _ who believe their nation was better off under the Third Reich. Frankfurter Rundschau newspaper reported a few days earlier that two West German journalists have written the first book since the fall of the Nazi dictatorship to examine how the German press aided <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s rise to power and his march through <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Other prominent newspapers carried recent articles by historians and jurists recounting <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s dictatorship and contrasting it with a recent rise in ultra-rightist politics. The left-leaning magazine Tempo reported Wednesday it had learned of plans by extremists to break windows at Jewish-owned businesses, send aloft a helium balloon emblazoned with the forbidden swastika and to lay a wreath at the Moenchengladbach birthplace of Nazi propaganda minister <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Goebbels </PERSON>. Tempo spokesman <PERSON> Carl-Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the magazine decided to report the details to alert possible victims, not to inform would-be agitators. Austrian police prepared to seal off access to <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s birthplace in the village of <LOCATION> Braunau </LOCATION> to prevent incidents But <PERSON> Butz </PERSON>, the West German <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said police reported only throngs of journalists at the scene as of midday Wednesday.
