however, reassured and encouraged about the directions'' after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> explained the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> approach. <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s role in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace process has diminished considerably since last summer, when <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> severed administrative and legal ties with Palestinians living in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. But a senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official who briefed reporters on Tuesday said <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s proximity to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> makes a Jordanian role in resolving the Palestinian issue inevitable. `` There is no way in the world that one can conceive of a peace process moving forward without the active involvement of King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>,'' said the official, insisting on anonymity. After a morning meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and a luncheon with Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> was to be guest of honor at a White House dinner tonight. Meetings with congressional leaders also were on his schedule. Two weeks ago, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> proposed during a visit here that Palestinians in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> elect representatives to negotiate with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> on limited self-government. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has endorsed the proposal on the condition that the elections lead to negotiations on the final status of the two territories. The senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said the proposal represents an attempt to end the impasse in the <LOCA