<HEAD>Cruise Ship Hits Boardwalk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADEIRA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A cruise ship rammed into a boardwalk, crunching a 35-foot section and damaging a waterside restaurant. No injuries were reported in Tuesday's accident, which sent dozens of people scrambling to safety. It was the second time in two months that a ship owned by <ORGANIZATION> Europa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cruise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> was involved in an accident in the same area. `` There was mass hysterics,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, who was sitting with his family at the Fisherman's Landing restaurant when they saw the ship headed for them. `` I said: Everybody, let's get out of here,' and we just dove out of the way.'' Seconds later, their corner table was crushed beneath pilings and planks. The Europa Sun pulled away from the boardwalk and docked safely within a few minutes. Europa officials said strong currents contributed to the crash, just as they said currents contributed to a March 11 accident involving the Sun's sister ship, the Europa Star. That accident damaged a commercial fishing boat. The Coast Guard found no mechanical problems with the vessel and allowed it to leave on an evening cruise a few hours later, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Brantley </PERSON> said. An investigation should take about a week, he said.
