<HEAD>Daphne du Maurier, Famed Romance Novelist, Dead at 81</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 11, `She spent...' to clarify that family did not
own mansion. Subs graf 19, `The story...' to CORRECT that story is about
woman, not man. Pickup 20th graf, `Histories, biographies...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Daphne </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurier </PERSON>, who became one of the century's most popular writers by mixing romance and the supernatural in `` Rebecca'' and other novels, died today. She was 81. <PERSON> Monty </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker-Munton </PERSON>, a family friend, trustee and executor, said he did not know the cause of death. `` For the last fortnight -LRB- two weeks -RRB- she'd just been in a gentle decline,'' he said. The author, who also wrote such popular classics as `` Frenchman's Creek'' and `` The Birds,'' died in her sleep at her home in the village of Par, in <LOCATION> Cornwall </LOCATION>, southwest <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Baker-Munton </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Baker-Munton </PERSON> said that at the novelist's request, her funeral would be private, with no memorial service or flowers and only close family and friends attending. He said the venue was not being disclosed. He said she would be cremated. Widowed in 1965, Mrs. <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurier </PERSON> for many years lived a secluded existence on the wild Cornish coast that inspired the settings for many of her works. She remained fit enough until a few weeks ago to take her dog for daily walks at the beach. Friendly and kind to her neighbors, she shunned publicity. `` She was a wonderful person with a great sense of fun. She never took herself too seriously. There was no grandeur about her famousness,'' said <PERSON> Baker-Munton </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON>, who knew her 44 years. `` I ca n't say I really like people,'' Mrs. <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurier </PERSON> once remarked. `` Perhaps that's why I always preferred to create my own instead of mixing with real ones.'' She spent the better part of her life producing bestsellers in <LOCATION> Menabilly </LOCATION>, the mansion on the Cornish coast where the family lived. Many of her novels were filmed, including `` The Birds,'' directed by <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON>. But she herself waited until the age of 64 before consenting to face a television interviewer. Born in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on May 13, 1907, <PERSON> Daphne </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurier </PERSON> was one of three daughters of the renowned actor Sir <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurier </PERSON>. She was educated by private tutors in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and at age 21 published her first articles and short stories. Her publisher told her: `` Write a novel,'' so she produced `` The Loving Spirit'' in 1931. The novel captivated a young British army major and led to a storybook courtship. The officer, <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, resolved to meet the author and journeyed to Par to find her. They met in 1932, married a few months later, and in the same year she published her second novel, `` I'll Never Be Young Again.'' She was just 25. `` It was rather woman's magazine-y,'' she remarked afterward. `` <ORGANIZATION> Jamaica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inn </ORGANIZATION>,'' another hit, followed in 1936, and then came `` <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>,'' her most famous work. Published in 1938, it became an instant hit, was turned into a film by <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON> starring <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Fontaine </PERSON>, and was reprinted 39 times, selling more than 1 million copies in hard cover alone. The story is about a young woman who marries an enigmatic widower and moves to his large country house, where she discovers that mystery surrounds his first wife's death. Trying to solve the mystery against the wishes of a sinister housekeeper, she is drawn into a terrifying psychological labyrinth. Histories, biographies, two plays and more novels followed, and altogether six of her novels were filmed. <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> became commander of British Airborne Forces in World War II and then treasurer to Prince <PERSON> Philip </PERSON>, husband of Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, as she became known when her husband was made a lord, wrote much of her work at <LOCATION> Menabilly </LOCATION>, the ancient Georgian manor the couple rented. Menabilly inspired <LOCATION> Manderley </LOCATION>, the name of the mansion in `` <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Cromwell </PERSON>'s troops gutted the house during the English Civil War, and legend had it that a cavalier was bricked up alive in one of Menabilly's gray stone buttresses. Her favorite hideaway was a gardener's hut, where, she said, `` I'd sit for hours on end, chain-smoking, chewing mints and tapping away at my typewriter.'' Angular, sharp-eyed, usually wearing slacks and sweaters, she would prowl the grounds of Menabilly or answer stacks of fan mail. After her husband died in 1965, she lived alone at Menabilly except for two <ORGANIZATION> Yorkshire </ORGANIZATION> terriers. Her son and two daughters visited frequently. In 1969 the queen made her a Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire, entitling her to call herself <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Daphne </PERSON>. That year she had to leave Menabilly when its owner returned, and she rented <PERSON> Kilmarth </PERSON>, her home in Par. There she wrote `` The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on the Strand.'' Menabilly still stands and is inhabited. In 1971 she published `` Not After Midnight,'' a collection of five novellas containing her special mix of romance and the eerie. In 1981 she published an autobiography, `` Growing Pains.''
