<HEAD>Seven Detainees Freed in South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven prominent anti-apartheid leaders detained for almost three years without charge were released today from a prison in the southern city of <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION>. Some of them were taken into custody at the beginning of the current state of emergency in June 1986, and the rest were detained later that year. All had joined hunger strikes by detainees earlier this year. Among those released today were the Rev. <PERSON> Sipho </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogola </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Interdenominational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lulu </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Students; and <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Neer </PERSON>, an official with the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions. All seven have held top positions in anti-apartheid groups around <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION>, one of the most militant black areas in the country. However, the highest-ranking opposition leaders in the area remain in detention. Since detainees began a hunger strike in January, the government says it has freed more than 800 people detained without charge and that less than 100 remain imprisoned. The government said previously that all emergency detainees had given up their hunger strikes. There was no way to independently confirm that report. More than 400 of the released detainees have been placed under restriction orders limiting their activities, according to human rights groups. An estimated 30,000 people, almost all black, have been held without charge for varying lengths of time under the state of emergency. The anti-apartheid activists are fighting a system that establishes a racially segregated society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The country's 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
