<HEAD>Kasparov Wins Adjourned Game, Moves a Half-Point Behind Ljubojevic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 World chess champion <PERSON> Garri </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> won his adjourned 16th round game Wednesday in the Chess World Cup and closed to a half-point of the leader, <PERSON> Ljubomir </PERSON> <PERSON> Ljubojevic </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, with one round left. In the endgame, <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>, playing black, outmaneuvered Spanish grandmaster <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Illescas </PERSON>. Facing an unstoppable checkmate, <PERSON> Illescas </PERSON> resigned. With the 17th and final round scheduled for Thursday, <PERSON> Ljubojevic </PERSON> has 10 -LCB- points out of a possible 15 and may become the first player in 7 -LCB- years to score more points than <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> in a competition. <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>, 26, is in second place with 10 points. Another Soviet grandmaster, <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Salov </PERSON>, is third with 9 -LCB- points. `` Before the tournament the big question was whether <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> would put in a wonderful performance and push his rating above <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> to become the highest ranked player in history,'' said <PERSON> Leontxo </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> chess commentator. `` Now the question is whether <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> will be able to catch <PERSON> Ljubojevic </PERSON>.'' In the final round, <PERSON> Ljubojevic </PERSON>, 38, will play with the disadvantageous black pieces against British grandmaster <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Short </PERSON>, the third-ranked player in the world, while <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> will face off with white against former world champion <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Spassky </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> is likely to face difficulties in facing <PERSON> Spassky </PERSON>, who has the reputation of one of the hardest players to defeat. A win scores one point and a draw a half point. The World Cup, a series of six tournaments held over two years featuring a prize fund of $ 1.2 million, is regarded as the second most important event in chess after the individual world championship. Each of 25 eligible grandmasters plays in four of the six competitions. The <ORGANIZATION> Barcelona </ORGANIZATION> event is fourth in the cycle. <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> won the second and thrid events in <LOCATION> Belfort </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, and is leading the competition. Former world champion <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>, who won the first tournament in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, is in second place. If <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> defeats <PERSON> Spassky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ljubojevic </PERSON> only draws with <PERSON> Short </PERSON>, they will tie for first place in the tournament. But a draw in his game Thursday will be enough to give <PERSON> Ljubojevic </PERSON> a victory in the separate World Cup points table, because <PERSON> Illescas </PERSON> is only competing in <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION> as a representative of the host country and is not eligible for the World Cup. When the World Cup calculations are made, all results against <PERSON> Illescas </PERSON> will be taken out. <PERSON> Ljubojevic </PERSON>, who drew <PERSON> Illescas </PERSON> in the eighth round, will have a half-point deducted from his final score, and <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> will lose a whole point. <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> has trailed in <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION> from the start. He scored only two draws in his first three games, going down in the third round to Soviet grandmaster <PERSON> Artur </PERSON> <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON>. In the other game completed Wednesday, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Belyavsky </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> defeated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grandmaster <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Seirawan </PERSON>. The final round will feature a battle between <PERSON> Salov </PERSON>, 24, and <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Korchnoi </PERSON>, a 58-year-old Soviet defector who plays for <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Korchnoi </PERSON> is fourth with nine points, a half-point behind <PERSON> Salov </PERSON>.
