<HEAD>Public Broadcasting Helps Fight Social Ills, Head Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Public broadcasting is a highly cost-effective way of helping solve national problems, <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> officials said Wednesday in defending a request for increased program funds and money to replace an aging satellite. Corporation president <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ledwig </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee that every dollar of federal funding to the organization now attracts nearly $ 6 in donations in corporate and audience donations. <PERSON> Ledwig </PERSON> also cited educational programs on public radio and television and the 13,000 hours a year in programming for the classroom that now reach 101 million TV viewers and more than 10 million radio listeners each week. `` Now is not the time to retreat,'' he said, when `` the public looks increasingly to public broadcasting to meet its needs for quality programming.'' He said that each federal dollar spent on an AIDS awareness program, for example, `` might save this committee thousands of dollars treating that patient.'' <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> is a private, nonprofit organization created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to support public broadcasting. It passes on about 71 percent of its operating budget to public radio and television stations. It gets its federal money two years in advance and is seeking $ 265 million for fiscal 1992. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration wants to freeze the corporation's appropriation at the 1991 level of $ 242 million and not provide any new money to replace a 10-year-old satellite that is expected to die in 1991 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has authorized $ 200 million for the satellite, but has appropriated just $ 56.8 million of that amount, in 1991. <PERSON> Ledwig </PERSON> said failure to replace the satellite would have a severe impact on programming funds that would have to be diverted to satellite construction. He also said congressional support for the full $ 265 million request `` is critical if <ORGANIZATION> CPB </ORGANIZATION> is to continue to increase the high standards of public broadcasting and to tap deeper into the potential that it holds for addressing many of this nation's most pressing problems.'' If the budget is frozen _ which means a cut, when inflation is counted _ the corporation loses the $ 6 in donations for each dollar cut, <PERSON> Ledwig </PERSON> said. Federal funds `` are the key dollars that bring in the others'' he said. Outlining something of a domino effect, <PERSON> Ledwig </PERSON> said that if the corporation's budget is cut, `` We start losing quality of the programming, we start losing audience, and we start losing contributions.'' The three subcommittee members in attendance each praised public broadcasting, but said it would be very difficult to increase spending given the current federal budget pinch. Subcommittee chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Natcher </PERSON>, D-Ky., asked how <PERSON> Ledwig </PERSON> could justify a request for a 9.5 percent spending hike <PERSON> Ledwig </PERSON> said the corporation was `` acutely aware'' of the competing demands on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for federal dollars. `` I believe, however, that federal support for public broadcasting is one of the most cost-effective means to address a number of critical problems facing the nation today.'' He said the corporation's 4.3 percent for administrative costs was the lowest of any agency in the government. Rep. <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, said he thought public broadcasters may be trying to mimic commercial television by paying high salaries to on-air personalities and $ 15,000 appearance fees to guests. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> was particularly concerned that <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Rukeyser </PERSON>, host of the popular `` Wall Street Week'' program, was being paid in six figures. `` Can you justify giving sombody three times as much salary ... than we pay a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justice?'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> asked. <PERSON> Ledwig </PERSON> said the show does not receive any funds from the corporation.
