<HEAD>Fourteen More Killed in Black Factional Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five days of factional fighting in <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION> has killed 14 blacks, including four who were ambushed by gunmen after getting off a bus, police and witnesses said Wednesday. More than 1,200 people have died during fighting between black factions since mid-1987, according to local groups. They say 165 of those victims were killed in the first three months of this year. Six people were killed Tuesday night in <LOCATION> Shongeni </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> between the southeastern cities of <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION>, the provincial capital, police said without providing details. Journalists saw three of the bodies. Two men and two women were killed Monday night in <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s Halt, a township outside <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION>, police also said. Witnesses and families said those victims had just alighted from a bus when gunmen sprang from the <PERSON> bush </PERSON> and fired at them. They said several other people were wounded. Residents said a man and a 13-year-old boy were shot in the same area Monday night and two other teen-agers were shot to death in their home outside <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION> on Friday. The main combatants in the fighting are the banned <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, the country's largest anti-apartheid coalition, and <ORGANIZATION> Inkatha </ORGANIZATION>, the political group of Zulu leader <PERSON> Mangosuthu </PERSON> <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON>. Both groups oppose apartheid, but their tactics differ. The front favors protests, boycotts, sanctions and other confrontational methods that Inkatha does not endorse. Some anti-apartheid activists accuse <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> of collaborating with the white-run government because he participates in the black homeland system.
