<HEAD>Pope Expresses Hope for Poland as Walesa Arrives in Rome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> prayed for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> on Wednesday as <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, his Solidarity union made legal again by the communist government, arrived to seek economic aid for his country and thank the pontiff for his help. At his public audience, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said in a prayer for success of his homeland's new political course: `` I pray to you, Lady of <PERSON> Jasna </PERSON> <PERSON> Gora </PERSON> ... the country will have new possibilities and that transformations will take place in the social, political, economic and moral life of the entire society.'' His reference was to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine. Solidarity, which <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> founded in 1980 as the Soviet bloc's first independent trade union, regained official status Monday <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> had a symbolic reconciliation Tuesday with the Polish leader, Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, who declared martial law in December 1981 to crush Solidarity. At <PERSON> Leonardo </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinci </PERSON> <PERSON> Airport </PERSON>, he told reporters: `` There is a great accord between society and the government. It is a political victory for all of us in Polish society, but for this victory to be complete we now have to take care of real issues and to get down to work together.'' The Polish government agreed in two months of negotiations with an opposition delegation led by Solidarity to legalize the union and create a freely elected <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as a second house of the Sejm, or parliament. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> hopes the result will be financial help from the West and Solidarity's cooperation in confronting the national economic crisis. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> met with Bishop <PERSON> Fiorenzo </PERSON> <PERSON> Angelini </PERSON>, chief of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> medical mission, and thanked him for aid the office gave Solidarity medical programs. <PERSON> Angelini </PERSON> pledged another $ 30,000. Later, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> attended a crowded Mass celebrated by four Polish bishops at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marian </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Trastevere </LOCATION> church. As the faithful received communion, two people unfurled a red-and-white Solidarity banner. The Solidarity leader has said he wants to encourage Western aid for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> during his three-day visit to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, which includes meetings with politicians and labor leaders. In <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s first public comment on the legalization of Solidarity, the pontiff prayed Wednesday that all involved in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s new political course would `` continue to demonstrate the courage, wisdom and calm indispensable to serving the public good.'' Addressing the <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> of <PERSON> Jasna </PERSON> <PERSON> Gora </PERSON>, he said: `` Today I want to thank you, oh <PERSON> Mother </PERSON>, for all the good that has grown from the experiences of that period'' when Solidarity was suppressed and outlawed. `` I give to your maternal care Solidarity, which today, after the new legalization of April 17, can return to activity.'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said he would ask <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> on Thursday `` to give his blessing to this difficult task of reform'' and said the pope `` has always been with us.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> warmly endorsed Solidarity when he met <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> in January 1981 at the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. The pontiff and the shipyard electrician met again during papal trips to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1983, the year <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> won the Nobel Peace Prize, and 1987. The church is a major force in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, a devoutly Roman Catholic country despite its communist government, and church representatives participated in the negotiations. In a clear illustration of Solidarity's change in status, the <LOCATION> Polish </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> met <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> at the airport.
