rators. `` It's difficult for them,'' he said of the soldiers More than 400 Palestinians have been killed in a violent uprising launched 17 months ago to protest <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 21-year rule of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> praised some recent Israeli measures such as the release of more than 450 Palestinian inmates, the unsealing of some houses blocked by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> forces as punitive measures, and the restoration of loudspeakers to Arab mosques. But he said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s `` record is still mixed,'' as shown by last week's shooting by security forces of at least five Palestinians in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village of <LOCATION> Nahalin </LOCATION>. Israeli military regulations allow soldiers to shoot plastic bullets at demonstrators fleeing the scene of a violent demonstration. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> spokesmen say plastic bullets are less lethal than other ammunition, but dozens of <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> have been killed _ some shot in the back _ because soldiers fired from closer than the required distance.
