<HEAD>New Coalition Announces Plans for Huge October Demonstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 60 national organizations announced plans Wednesday for a huge march on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Oct. 7 to demand more federal housing assistance for the nation's homeless. `` This is n't a march so much as it is a calling forth of the human spirit,'' declared a tearful <PERSON> Valerie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, the actress and longtime homeless activist. `` It's an expression of who we are as human beings.'' She addressed a marathon news conference at which dozens of prominent civil rights, labor, church and anti-poverty leaders announced the creation of a `` Housing Now!'' umbrella organization and plans for the march in October. At least 63 nationwide organizations are participating. They include the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> YWCA </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rainbow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, headed by The Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Zigas </PERSON>, a principal organizer of the march and president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Low-Income </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, predicted that `` hundreds of thousands'' of people would participate. Famed homeless activist <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> noted that `` I was 6 years old when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed legislation calling for safe and affordable housing for all Americans. Well, I'm 45 now. And it's time to remind one another that the wealthiest nation on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> has the resources, but simply lacks the will, to get the job done. <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, Mayor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, speaking for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>, blamed the homeless problem on the abandonment of the federal housing assistance policies of the 1960s and 1970s. `` If we had continued those policies,'' he said, `` about 1.8 million more households would be receiving housing assistance _ or enough to accommodate 4 million people. It's no coincidence that there are 3 million homeless in this country,'' he declared. Since 1981, budget authority for all federal housing assistance programs has been cut by more than 75 percent _ from $ 32 billion to less than $ 8 billion a year, according to the new coalition. It said only about 1 out of every 4 eligible poor renters actually receives a federal housing subsidy. <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> noted also that the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> estimates than more than 24 million people spend more than half of their income on housing. `` That's a disgrace,'' he said. The joint `` call to action'' issued by the coalition complained that `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> hides behind the budget deficit when it comes to housing our people. We call on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to recognize housing as the immediate national priority it must become.'' `` We can not deny,'' said actor <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Voight </PERSON>, `` that wherever we step, we step over a human being lying helplessly in our streets. Unless we act now, our streets will be littered with them.'' `` We are sitting on our hands, and more and more people are suffering,'' said <PERSON> Louisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Stark </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> for the Homeless. She cited a recent <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> study which indicated that by the year 2,000, there will be an estimated 19 million homeless Americans, barring a change in policy.
