<SECOND>AM-Elderly-Drugs,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>HHS Official Says Medicare Computer System Could Guard Against Drug
Reactions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new prescription drug benefit program being readied for 32 million Medicare beneficiaries offers a golden opportunity to include safeguards against adverse reactions that hospitalize at least 200,000 elderly people a year, witnesses told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel Wednesday. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON>, inspector general for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, told the committee that it would be `` stupid'' for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to be so insistent on enforcing an arbitrary deadline for setting up a computer-based billing system that it closes off the possibility of building in the safeguards. The idea, he said, is to program the Medicare computer system that will link the nation's pharmacies so that the pharmacist filling a doctor's prescription will be able to tell on the spot whether the patient is taking another drug that could react with the new one. Some private pharmacy chains already use such programs, often citing them in advertising as a reason to shop at a particular pharmacy. <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON> was called before the subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging to elaborate on a study that has found the Medicare program paid at least $ 500 million in 1987 for hospital admissions that were related to an adverse prescription drug reaction or an overdose. He told the panel that is a conservative figure because hospitals do not always flag drug reaction cases in the records they submit for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> reimbursements. Preliminary results from the report released previously found that the elderly account for 200,000, or 39 percent, of all hospitalizations from drug reactions and half of deaths from such reactions. <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON>, who has referred to the situation as `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s other drug problem,'' said he is concerned that the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is feeling so much congressional pressure to meet have a prescription drug billing system up and running well before the 1991 startup of the program that it will design a system that precludes adding computerized crosschecks of various medications a Medicare beneficiary may already be taking. `` I think that would be stupid and I would hate to see that happen,'' he said. Beginning in 1991, <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> will pay 50 percent of drug costs after a $ 600 annual deductible. The government payment rises to 60 percent the following year and 80 percent in 1993 _ also after a $ 600 deduction. Suggesting that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was not entirely clear in the instructions it gave <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> on how to set up a national system to keep track of Medicare drug claims, <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON> said, `` My concern is that we will rush ahead to create a data base driven solely by financial record-keeping concerns and neglect the quality of care issue.'' Heading off drug reactions before they occur would save money in the long run by cutting down hospitalization costs for treating the victims of such episodes, he said. Almost all adverse prescription drug reactions stem from patients not properly following directions for taking the medicine or taking different medicines that can react with each other _ either drugs they are prescribed by different physicians or by a single physician who does n't know any better. Food and Drug Administrator <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> supported <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON> in calling for a <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> computer system that provides a way to crosscheck prescriptions. `` We think this is a golden opportunity,'' said <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. `` We fear it may be implemented without including a way to do this.''
</TEXT>
