<HEAD>Jury Weighs Life Or Death For Shopping Center Killer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prosecutor asked jurors Wednesday to reject defense claims of temporary insanity and recommend the death penalty for a man convicted of killing six people in a shopping center shooting spree. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> left `` a killing field'' behind him in the two <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> shopping centers where he also tried to kill 24 others in 1987, State Attorney <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfinger </PERSON> told jurors. `` May God have mercy on the defendant's soul for his cruel and atrocious and uncaring acts,'' <PERSON> Wolfinger </PERSON> said in his final argument. `` Evidence has shown that this defendant has forfeited his right to live on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. `` He is a cold, calculating killer. He deserves to die.'' <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> demonstrated that he was in total control of his mental faculties when he methodically tracked down and shot at his victims repeatedly, some of them while they lay wounded and moaning, <PERSON> Wolfinger </PERSON> said. There was premeditation because `` his plan was to kill, kill, kill. He meant to do it and he did it,'' he said. Public defenders representing the 61-year-old former librarian were to present their final arguments later. The jurors who convicted <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> on April 5 of 32 counts of murder, attempted murder and kidnapping now have to recommend his punishment: death or life in prison without possibility of parole for 25 years. The verdict can be by simple majority rather than unanimously. Circuit Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Antoon </PERSON> said he would give `` great weight'' to the panel's recommendation, but he does not have to accept it in passing either sentence. The state attorney held up a shotgun used in the wounding of a teen-ager across the street from <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON>'s house. <PERSON> Wolfinger </PERSON> pumped the weapon several times in front of the jury. He then held up the semiautomatic assault rifle used in the shopping center rampage, popping in a 30-round clip several times. Anticipating defense arguments that <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> was insane at the time of the April 23, 1987, shootout, the prosecutor said: `` There has never been any disagreement over mental illness. The only disagreement is its effect'' and how much of a role it played in the crimes. The defense tried to present `` every conceivable, so-called bizarre incident'' in <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON>'s life, <PERSON> Wolfinger </PERSON> said, and it wanted the jury to feel that `` he should be relieved of all responsibility for that crime.'' As to arguments about the defendant's delusions over homosexuality, <PERSON> Wolfinger </PERSON> said: `` What we have here is a man who ca n't accept the doubts of his own masculinity ... and blamed it on everyone else.''
