<HEAD>Soviet Says Moscow Will Open Airways to Foreign TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> promised a 35-nation East-West conference on press freedom Wednesday that it would review working conditions for Moscow-based journalists and open its airways to foreign TV programs. The chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegate accused four of the communist participants _ <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> _ of ignoring the agreement on press and other freedoms that the 35 countries signed in January at the Conference on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The signatory countries varied from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where press freedom is enshrined in the constitution, to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, where typewriters have to be licensed and police keep records of the typefaces. The aim of this week's meeting, Information Forum, is to monitor compliance with the agreement. Ambassador <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marks </PERSON>, a former director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and head of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> delegation, said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had made substantial progress, including stopping jamming foreign broadcasts, but its media remained only `` semi-free.'' `` The concept that the East Europeans and the Soviets had that the government controls the press is now disappearing ... some -LRB- non-official -RRB- viewpoints are presented, not all,'' <PERSON> Marks </PERSON> said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` But we're going to be behind them. The objectives are to have a free press, not a semi-free press.'' Soviet deputy foreign minister <PERSON> Vladimi