<FIRST>r w AM-SmokeTests     04-19 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoke Tests,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Near Capitol Tests Smoke-Control System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> burned 500 pounds of wood in an old <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> hotel Wednesday in an experiment to help decide whether it's worthwhile to try to control smoke in building fires. The institute's system confined smoke from the fire to one floor of the seven-story brick building, which was studded throughout with more than 100 temperature-measuring devices and other instruments measuring air pressure and gas concentrations. The institute, known until recently as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION>, is part of the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Smoke control systems have come into increasing use in office buildings over the past decade, but officials of the institute said such systems had not been challenged extensively by real fires. What systems there are have been constructed according to theoretical calculations and rules of thumb drawn up by fire experts. The cause of many fire fatalities is listed as `` smoke inhalation,'' which frequently may be carbon monoxide from incomplete combustion or other toxic gases given off by a fire. Much of the $ 40 billion in annual property damage from fires also results from smoke, and `` it does n't take much to gum up your computer disks'' even if the flames never get close, observed <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Snell </PERSON>, director of the institute's <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. `` The big question in the fire protection field is, Does smoke control work? And under what circumstances does it make sense to add it to building requirements?'' <PERSON> Snell </PERSON> told reporters attending the demonstration burn at the old Plaza Hotel between the Capitol and Union Station. The building is to be demolished. Some experts question whether sprinkler-protected buildings need a smoke control system. To work properly, such systems must supply air to the fire, which may make it grow `` and these are the tradeoffs,'' said <PERSON> Snell </PERSON>. Smoke control works by using a building's existing air-handling system to pressurize the stairwells and the floors above and below the fire floor. Existing fire sensors can be used to trigger the proper arrangement of fans. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Building </ORGANIZATION> and the Madison Building of the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have smoke control systems. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Klute </PERSON>, director of Wednesday's experiment, said such systems should add `` a small fraction'' to the cost of ventilation systems. In Wednesday's test, 2,000 cubic-feet-per-minute fans pumped air into the first and third floors of the hotel while a fan of the same size withdraw air from the second floor, where a pyre of 2 inch-by-2 inch fir sticks burned in a fireproofed room about 10 feet by 11 feet in front of an open windown about four feet square. A fan of 9,000 cubic feet per minute pressurized the single stairwell in the building. The open window made it `` the most severe test so far,'' said <PERSON> Klute </PERSON>. This meant the difference in air pressure between the fire floor and the adjacent floors would be about half the difference recommended for current smoke control schemes. Flames and black smoke denoting incomplete combustion poured out of the open window and licked the window above. At one point, the temperature sensor closest to the fire indicated 2,696 degrees Fahrenheit, and the carbon monoxide content of the hallway was shown as almost 0.5 percent _ half what it had been in previous tests of fires in the hallway with all windows closed. But television monitors on every floor and every landing of the stairwell showed no smoke throughout the test, even though the second-floor hallway was full of opaque smoke above a few inches off the floor at 6 minutes 43 seconds after ignition, and completely full shortly after that.
</TEXT>
