<HEAD>Philippine Vice President Says He's `Jobless'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> vice president at odds with President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, described himself on Wednesday as being in `` a state of suspended animation'' as he prepares a bid for his nation's top office. Laurel, who spoke with reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, is visiting <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to meet with congressional leaders and highlight his views in advance of next month's national convention of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Nacionalista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He has said he expects to be one of several candidates who are going to `` throw their hat in the ring'' for the 1992 presidential elections. Although Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has said she will not seek re-election, it is possible that she may be drafted to run again. Relations are so poor between Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> and her vice president that they do not speak. Although <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> said his visit was not geared around criticism at Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, the majority of his statements found fault with her government's battle against the nation's 20-year-old communist insurgency, as well as the approach to economic and political development. In contrast to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> system of government, the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> vice president has no duties under the constitution unless appointed to a position by the president. After a political falling out in 1987, <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> resigned his post as foreign minister and lately has been organizing an opposition party. `` I'm in a state of suspended animation,'' he said. Still, he quipped, `` as a jobless vice president, I'm able to travel more than others'' and visit with citizens. As for the insurgency, <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> said rebel numbers have ballooned from 14,000 to 33,000 in the past three years. `` If we do n't put up a responsible, democratic opposition, the alternative we face is a violent opposition,'' he said. A <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official familiar with the situation in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> said, however, that the insurgency was not that large and that it `` has n't made any particular progress'' over the past several years. The official commented on condition he not be named. The vice president also said he differed with Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> on the issue of the negotiation of the future of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and he criticized a lack of movement on the issue. He argued that the Philippine government should enter into negotiations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as soon as possible, since the pact expires in 1991. <PERSON> Laruel </PERSON> did say Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> deserved credit for helping the nation through a rocky three years since former dictator <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> left the country. A civilian-military uprising in February 1986 ended <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' rule and swept Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> and Laurel into power. But <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> argued that `` the transition from dictatorship to democracy'' wo n't be complete without the formation of a `` responsible, legitimate, organized opposition,'' which he said his party intends to be.
