<FIRST>r a AM-FastDay     04-19 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fast Day,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Hampshire Observes Unique `Fast Day'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> residents will have a long weekend thanks to a state holiday born in 1681 out of fear that its first governor was going to die. Monday is Fast Day. Until four years ago, the fourth Monday in April was observed widely as a spring Thanksgiving, with all state offices closed. But the state's contract with its workers now has made Fast Day a `` floating holiday,'' an optional day off that allows state offices to stay open. Although state offices will be open, some city and town offices will close, schools and banks will close, federal offices will be open and stores will have sales. Fast Day began with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cutt </PERSON>, about whom little is known other than he was `` President of the Royal Province of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> by grace of <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>,'' and that he sometimes spelled his name <PERSON> Cutts </PERSON>. Cutt was the richest merchant in <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION>, the colonial capital. On May 6, 1680, when he was 60, he had a foreboding of his death and wrote his will. By next year, the Welsh immigrant was so ill that the colonial <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> declared a day of `` fasting, humiliation and prayer'' for his recovery. It was a peculiarly <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> custom to declare days of fasting and prayer whenever the colonists felt threatened by catastrophe. The first known fast day was observed by <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> after the drought of 1622. In 1894, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> substituted Fast Day with Patriots Day to observe the start of the Revolutionary War. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> observe Patriots Day on the third Monday in April. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>'s theological cure for Cutt failed. He died on April 1, 1681. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> used to observe as many as three Fast Days a year. By 1899, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> decided on one and in 1949, with a view toward a three-day weekend, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> settled on the fourth Monday in April. The nature of the observance has changed. Church attendance used to be mandatory. The 10-shilling fine against those taking part in `` labor, business or work of their ordinary calling'' was lifted long ago. Recreation no longer is forbidden. Now the holiday comes as <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>'s long winter gives way to spring, when snow tires and storm windows are packed away in garages, when schools begin a week of vacation, and when golf courses become snow-free.
</TEXT>
