<HEAD>Iraelis Commemorate Exodus From Egypt; Police On Alert</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israelis gathered for festive meals Wednesday to begin Passover, the holiday commemorating the liberation of the ancient Israelites from slavery. Security forces were on high alert in case of guerrilla attacks. Thousands of people went to resorts on the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> and Sea of <LOCATION> Galilee </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, secular Israelis jammed beaches and outdoor restaurants. Army and police alerts were ordered because the 16-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories increased fear of guerrilla attacks during the holiday. The army stepped up its forces to prevent infiltrations across <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s borders. Since January, 31 guerrillas have been killed in a dozen attacks along the border with <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Police were out in force in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s walled <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to prevent disruptions of religious services, a national police spokesman said. In downtown <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, police discovered a small explosive device in a paint bucket left on the sidewalk near a cafe, but experts defused it, police spokesman <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandori </PERSON> reported. Passover, which commemorates the flight of the Israelites from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, began at sundown Wednesday with a traditional meal known as the seder. It includes such symbolic foods as bitter herbs to remind Jews of the harshness of their enslavement, and an unleavened bread called matzoh. During the week-long holiday many Jews abstain from bread, beer and other products made with yeast to remember the Israelites, who left <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> so quickly they had no time to leaven their bread. The holiday derives its name from the book of Exodus, which recounts that God `` passed over'' the homes of Israelites when meting out the worst of 10 plagues, and killed the first-born of every Egyptian. The plagues forced the pharaoh to let the Jews leave <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> participated in a symbolic outdoor seder organized by Soviet Jewish activists to thank the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for supporting Soviet Jews who have been refused permission to emigrate. Organizers set up a table on the sidewalk across the street from the embassy, serving wine and traditional Passover dishes. The army served Passover meals at military bases, but soldiers serving in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> were given grape juice instead of the traditional four cups of red wine, an army spokesman said. In a goodwill gesture for the holiday, more than 700 prisoners serving time for criminal offenses were given forloughs of two to four days, said <PERSON> Shuli </PERSON> <PERSON> Meiri </PERSON>, a prison services spokeswoman.
