<HEAD>Rules Proposed to Speed States in Child-Support Enforcement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government proposed regulations Wednesday designed to force states to pursue child support more vigorously by requiring them to supply information for collection orders promptly. `` In the past, some states have not given sufficient attention'' to such efforts, said Health and Human Srvices Secretary <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. `` Millions of children have suffered because of this lack of attention.'' Delay in action by the states, he said, has prevented children from receiving financial support they are due. The regulations, which implement the Family Support Act passed last year by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in a major welfare overhaul, sets time limits for states to respond to requests for assistance in establishing and enforcing child support orders. Limits would be established for opening and maintaining case records, locating absent parents, establishing paternity, enforcing support obligations and receiving and distributing support payments. The regulations also provide criteria for states to use in determining whether to close a child support case. States would be required to comply with those time limits by Oct. 1, 1990. The regulations were published in Wednesday's Federal Register. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> set a 60-day comment period, after which the department will issue final rules.
