dan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an agency of the rebel army. Ms. <PERSON> Weathers </PERSON> said they were armed. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said use of Operation Lifeline's overland route to <LOCATION> Torit </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Kapoeta </LOCATION> would be suspended indefinitely but an airlift to <LOCATION> Torit </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Entebbe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION>, would begin Friday. Operations officer <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Torit </LOCATION>'s population had grown from 3,000 to 25,000 as displaced southern Sudanese seeking food and shelter arrived from the <PERSON> bush </PERSON>, and was expected to reach 50,000 in a few weeks. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> had planned to move 25,000 tons of food and supplies from <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> to southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> before the rains, but convoys have taken only 120 tons to <LOCATION> Kapoeta </LOCATION> so far. Norwegian People's Aid, in conjunction with World Vision of <LOCATION> Monrovia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, has trucked several thousand tons of food to <LOCATION> Kapoeta </LOCATION> since October in another relief effort. An airlift from <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION> operated by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> has carried 3,000 tons of food and other supplies to <LOCATION> Juba </LOCAT