state. Elsewhere, the sky was clear from the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> across the <LOCATION> central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>. Most of the western half of the nation had afternoon temperatures in the 60s and 70s, up into the 90s in the desert Southwest. Behind the cold front, temperatures were in the 40s and 50s from the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> across the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and Great Lakes to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and scattered frost was forecast overnight in northern <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 41 degrees at <LOCATION> Sault </LOCATION> Ste. <PERSON> Marie </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, to 99 at <LOCATION> Gila </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bend </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>. Wednesday's low in the 48 contiguous states was 19 degrees at <LOCATION> Gunnison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. For Thursday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast along the <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> coast, across southern <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and over much of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, and over the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Rain was forecast across the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>. Highs in the 50s and 60s were predicted over the Great Lakes region and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, with some 40s in extreme northern sections; in the 60s in the Appalachians and along the mid <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, and along much of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>; in the 90s in southwestern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and sections of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>; around 100 in the desert <ORGANIZATI