<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Daphne </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurier </PERSON>, author of `` <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>,'' died Wednesday at her home in <LOCATION> Cornwall </LOCATION>, the wildly beautiful English province in which she set many of her celebrated novels of romance and the supernatural. She was 81. Her novels like `` <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>,'' `` Frenchman's <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>,'' `` My Cousin <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON>,'' and `` <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> Inn'' were household names in popular fiction and became hit movies. The du Maurier style, vivid and gothic, made for spine-chilling films like <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON>'s `` The Birds,'' from her short story, and <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Roeg </PERSON>'s `` Do n't Look Now,'' from her novella. <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Daphne </PERSON>, as she was known after being honored by Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, died in her sleep, said her friend and legal executor, <PERSON> Monty </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker-Munton </PERSON>. Until about two weeks ago, she had been fit enough for daily walks with her dog around Par, the <PERSON> Cornish </PERSON> village where she had lived in widowed seclusion for 20 years. <PERSON> Daphne </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurier </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on May 13, 1907, one of three daughters of the renowned actor Sir <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurier </PERSON>. Educated by private tutors in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, she was 21 when she published her first articles and short stories. Her first novel, `` The Loving Spirit,'' appeared in 1931. The novel captivated a young British army major and led to a storybook courtship. The officer, <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> `` Boy'' <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, resolved to meet the young woman and journeyed to Par to find her. They met in 1932 and married a few months later. `` It was rather woman's magazine-y,'' she remarked afterward. In the same year she published her second novel, `` I'll Never be Young Again.'' `` <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inn </LOCATION>,'' a big seller, followed in 1936, and then came `` <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>.'' `` <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>,'' about a young bride whose probing into the death of her husband's previous wife leads her into a frightening psychological labyrinth, was published in 1938 and sold 1 million copies in hard cover alone. It was reprinted 39 times, launched <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s movie career opposite <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Fontaine </PERSON>, and was translated worldwide. She became <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> with the ennoblement of her husband, who had been commander of British Airborne Forces in World War II and then treasurer to Prince <PERSON> Philip </PERSON>, husband of Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. In 1943, they rented Menabilly, the rambling, often fog-shrouded Georgian manor which had inspired <LOCATION> Manderley </LOCATION>, the fire-doomed mansion in `` <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Cromwell </PERSON>'s troops gutted the house during the English Civil War, and legend had it that a cavalier was bricked up alive in one of Menabilly's gray stone buttresses. The writer's hideaway was a gardener's hut, where, she said, `` I'd sit for hours on end, chain-smoking, chewing mints and tapping away at my typewriter.'' She would prowl the grounds of Menabilly or answer stacks of fan mail when not at work on her writing. Her husband died in 1965. In 1969, <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Daphne </PERSON>, as she had become that year, moved from <LOCATION> Menabilly </LOCATION> to Par with her two <ORGANIZATION> Yorkshire </ORGANIZATION> terriers and rented another mansion, <LOCATION> Kilmarth </LOCATION>. `` It is rather like death to have to leave,'' she said. Despite her wealth, she never owned a home. At <LOCATION> Kilmarth </LOCATION> she wrote `` The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on the Strand.'' Her last novel was `` Rule Britannia,'' published in 1972. `` Growing Pains,'' a memoir of her early years, appeared in 1981, and her introduction to a new book on <LOCATION> Cornwall </LOCATION> will appear in the fall. Although always cheerful and kind to friends, she preferred a secluded life. `` I ca n't say I really like people,'' she once remarked. `` Perhaps that's why I always preferred to create my own instead of mixing with real ones.'' She waited until age 64 before consenting to be interviewed on TV. <PERSON> Baker-Munton </PERSON> said she would be cremated later this week at a private ceremony with no flowers and only family friends, her son and two daughters, in accordance with her wishes.
