<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dominitchi </PERSON> <PERSON> Demeter </PERSON>, considered a king among Gypsies, died at a hospital where hundreds of his followers flocked upon hearing of his illness, police and hospital officials said. <PERSON> Demeter </PERSON>, 57, was admitted last week to the <ORGANIZATION> Mulhouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, suffering from cerebral congestion. He was in a coma when he died Tuesday night, a hospital spokesman said. About 700 <PERSON> Romany </PERSON> <PERSON> Gypsies </PERSON> of Hungarian origin had gathered in the <LOCATION> Mulhouse </LOCATION> region in eastern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> when they heard that the Gypsy leader, known as <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Demeter </PERSON>, was ill. More than 100 caravans were parked Wednesday at an unused mine in nearby <LOCATION> Wittenheim </LOCATION> The hospital spokesman said hundreds of Gypsies filed through the hospital over the last few days to pay respects to <ORGANIZATION> Demeter </ORGANIZATION>. A special telephone line was installed to take care of phone calls by followers in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and abroad inquiring about his condition, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity. `` <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Demeter </PERSON> had a considerable audience among the Gypsy diaspora,'' said a police official, also speaking anonymously. `` The entire community, from all continents, was following the agony of the patriarch.'' A police spokesman said <ORGANIZATION> Demeter </ORGANIZATION>'s body would be transported Thursday to the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> region, accompanied, in the Gypsy tradition, by an all-male escort. The body was to be buried on Friday, but the exact burial site was not immediately known.
