<HEAD>Anxious Families Gather To Wait For News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf, ``The longer ..., to include
Navy policy on notification, release of identities to news media.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Battleship Explosion, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Families of crew members aboard the USS Iowa gathered Wednesday at a <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> gym to await word about loved ones who were on the ship when a gun turret packed with gunpowder exploded in flames. `` The major problem is lack of information,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Chaplain <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Brimhall </PERSON>, who was with the families. `` They are very, very frustrated. For those who had husbands or sons in the area of the explosion, they are wondering, ` Was it my husband, my son?''' `` The longer we hear nothing, the better it is,'' said <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, a relative of crewman <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> policy requires that families of dead or injured sailors be notified before any list of victims is released to the news media, and not all families had been notified by mid-evening Wednesday, officials said. <PERSON> Brimhall </PERSON> was one of many <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> chaplains, social workers, and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> personnel called in to deal with the families' grief. `` The first thing we did was establish a place for them to gather,'' said Master Chief <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinder </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. `` We provide a place for them to be. The chaplains, social workers, <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and others are there to help them in any way possible.'' `` Our primary purpose,'' <PERSON> Brimhall </PERSON> said, `` is to help them air their feelings, talk about their fears to reassure them, but be honest. Some are going to loose a loved one. It is a ministry of presence.'' The families were helping each other, <PERSON> Brimhall </PERSON> said. `` There is a lot of support within the group. I saw relationships develop right before my eyes as women put their arms around those who were having touble,'' he said. He described the mood in the gym as varied. `` There are those who are really struggling and those who are really stoic,'' he said. <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Quagliotti </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brownton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said she and her husband had n't been able to reach <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials to find out about her son, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Quagliotti </PERSON>, a dentist on the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> `` I have no idea where our son could be,'' Ms. <PERSON> Quagliotti </PERSON> said. `` Anything is possible.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s contingency plan for such tragedies was worked out long before the accident, <PERSON> Kinder </PERSON> said. `` We take this very seriously. Family response crisis is a very major issue with us,'' he said. <PERSON> Kinder </PERSON> said the families are given updates at least every half hour, and more often as developments warrant. `` Right now, for some of these families, they would rather have bad news than no news at all,'' <PERSON> Brimhall </PERSON> said.
