<FIRST>r a AM-LucilleBall-Heart     04-19 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucille Ball-Heart,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ball Among 2,000 Americans Hospitalized Yearly For Split Aorta Wall</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lucille Ball</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY50</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 2,000 Americans are hospitalized annually with a split wall in the body's major artery, an ailment that sent <PERSON> Lucille </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON> into emergency heart surgery, a heart specialist said Wednesday. `` It's one of the most severely painful diseases a human has to suffer,'' although not everyone who gets an `` aortic dissection'' experiences extreme pain, said Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, chief of cardiac diseases at the National Heart, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, Md. The condition, also called a `` dissecting aortic aneurysm,'' involves a tear that splits the wall of the aorta, the main artery connecting the heart to smaller arteries that carry blood throughout the body. Although 2,000 Americans reach hospitals and are diagnosed with a split aorta each year, an unknown number of others suffer the ailment and have it misdiagnosed as a heart attack or die before they arrive at an emergency room, <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said during a telephone interview. He estimated aortic dissection kills about half of those it afflicts, often when the split aorta wall ruptures to cause internal hemorrhaging. Of those who reach hospitals and undergo surgery, about three-fourths survive hospitalization. Death is most likely during the operation itself, he added. The aorta emerges from the left ventricle _ the heart's main pumping chamber _ passes upward and arches over the top of the heart, then passes down behind the heart and into the abdomen. During aortic dissection, a tear suddenly develops in the tissue that makes up the wall of the aorta. The layers of tissue separate, allowing blood to flow into the gap, which then painfully expands like a balloon. The pressure can make the tear spread up or down a greater length of the artery. An aortic dissection is different than the much more common and conventional aortic aneurysm, in which the artery wall is weakened and balloons outward, but layers of the artery wall do n't split. `` In Miss <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>'s condition, the beginning portion of her aorta -LRB- near the heart -RRB- began to tear apart, and that tearing progressed all the way down into her abdomen,'' her surgeon, Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kass </PERSON>, said Tuesday night. The split wall `` involved essentially her whole aorta,'' he added. During the six-hour operation at <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Kass </PERSON> said, he removed the 77-year-old Miss <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>'s ascending aorta _ the short stretch of aorta that emerges from the ventricle _ and the aortic valve. He replaced them with those taken from the cadaver of a 27-year-old. The aortic valve controls the flow of blood from the ventricle into the aorta. <PERSON> Kass </PERSON> said the expansion in Miss Ball's split artery wall `` unroofed the aortic valve'' to make it leak. A leaky valve can cause heart failure because blood ca n't be pumped out of the heart efficiently. During a news conference, <PERSON> Kass </PERSON> did n't explain why the rest of the aorta was n't replaced. But <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said many arteries branch off the aorta, so it's safest to replace only the part where the tear started A surgeon can `` tack'' together the place where the split wall continues, preventing ballooning by blocking blood from flowing into the gap, he said. <PERSON> Kass </PERSON> also said he detached the ends of Miss Ball's coronary arteries where they connected to her ascending aorta, then reattached them to the newly implanted aorta, restoring blood flow that nourishes the heart. Sometimes an aorta with a split wall is n't replaced, but is repaired with synthetic materials, such as by inserting a knitted Dacron tube inside the defective section of aorta. Doctors do n't know why aortic walls sometimes split. Hardening of the arteries and congenital artery weakness have been suspected. But the risk is increased by high blood pressure, which <PERSON> Kass </PERSON> said Miss Ball has suffered for several years.
</TEXT>
