<HEAD>Shareholders Reject Lending Resolution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> shareholders have overwhelmingly rejected requests from church groups led by the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and representatives of South African Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> to sever all remaining ties with racially segregated <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest banking company, stopped doing business in that country two years ago when it sold its <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> N.A </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary to <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s largest bank, for about $ 65 million. But <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, like some other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks, still has about $ 666 million in private outstanding loans to South African borrowers. It recently agreed to extend by 10 years payments on the bulk of that debt, and accept partial principal payment as part of an agreement with other international banks. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> had placed a temporary moratorium on principal payments of bank debt in September 1985. The church groups had asked that <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, which remains the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial bank creditor of that country, to refuse to reschedule South African debt and make any new loans as long as the present political system remains intact. `` By extending this debt we're expressing a tolerance of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Tuesday at <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>'s annual shareholders meeting. `` We must make a moral judgment.'' <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> said that while his company opposes <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s apartheid system `` debt forgiveness is a word you'll never hear from this bank. `` Our objective is simple and straightforward: We would like to be paid back. It's not a question of morals ... it's a question of business judgment,'' he explained. <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> shareholders also agreed, with 91.6 percent of them voting against a proposal to abandon debt rescheduling agreements with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, vs. 8.4 percent approving it. The remaining abstained. The shareholders also rejected a request by the church groups for <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> to end corresponent banking with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, in which it performs services for firms not having access to direct facilities. The vote was 89.2 percent opposed, 10.8 percent in agreement and the rest abstaining.
