<HEAD>Teacher Gets Kids Rappin' Economics With `RUN G.N.P.'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON> has been teaching long enough to know that kids are n't exactly wild about learning economics. So he came up with a novel way of presenting the often-dry curriculum: through the lyrics of rap music. <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON>, who has dabbled in the music business as a performer and manager during his 18 years as a public school teacher, wrote and recorded `` RUN G.N.P.,'' a rappin' tribute to the joys of economics. He also had some of his students at Martin Luther King Jr.. Middle School participate in making a video version of the song <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON> uses both as motivational tools to make economics seem less imposing to the 6th -, 7th - and 8th-grade students in his social studies and history Rather than the academic words of a textbook, <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON> believes teachers could better introduce young students to economic concepts with such lines as: `` Try to maximize profits Minimize costs That's what I'm tryin' to do Increase productivity Improve the quality So I can bring the best product to you.'' Or how about this explanation of supply and demand: `` Now, when resources get scarce or demand increases the price of goods rise it rarely decreases. People's tastes change and so do I If I want to stay in business I'd better comply.'' And, you can dance to it. `` I thought it was a good idea in this day and age, when kids can rap and memorize pages and pages of -LRB- entertainment -RRB- information, why not do something educational to go along with it,'' <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON> said in a recent interview. `` Economics is sometimes boring and difficult,'' he said. `` I saw this would be a really nice idea. Hell, I write music, songs _ I said let me put something together.'' <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON>, 40, recorded the song, whose title was inspired by rap stars <ORGANIZATION> RUN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D.M.C. </ORGANIZATION>, with a small group of professional musicians. He hopes to release it as a single for use by other teachers. The video, set in a city park, has the ragged feel of a home movie, but <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON> said he'd like to make a more polished version if he can obtain money to cover production costs. Economics is just a small part of the middle school curriculum. But <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON> believes that if his musical efforts are successful, students will be more inclined toward the subject when they reach high school. `` Kids in high school really put it off ... it's something that really has a low priority,'' <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON> said. `` We try to dispel the myths, so it's not a terrible monster. `` It can ba a lot of fun, economics can be made easy,'' he added. `` When they get into economics is high school, they're gon na say, ` Yeah.''' <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON> said the seeds of his idea were planted a couple of years ago when he enrolled in a program at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> that stressed creative and unusual approaches to teaching. Mixing music and economics was a natural for him, <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON> said. `` I've always been into motivating the kids through music,'' said <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON>, who in the 1970s managed the career of the late blues singer <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON>. `` I used to bring in Willie Guy during Black History Month, and he was the most effective,'' he said. <PERSON> Kapstein </PERSON> said he has other ideas, but for now he's waiting to see if `` RUN G.N.P.'' catches on. `` If things take off, I'll be turning out songs like crazy,'' he said.
