<SECOND>PM-Aging Turboprops,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firm Says Turboprop Fleet Younger Than Jetliner Fleet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Aircraft Order, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The average age of planes in the fleet of turboprop aircraft used by airlines in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is 3.1 years younger than the average for the jetliner fleet, says an aviation consulting firm. The average age of turboprop aircraft used by airlines in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is 9.3 years, while the average age of jet aircraft is 12.4 years, according to a study released Tuesday by <ORGANIZATION> Avmark </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which appraises aircraft throughout the world. The report prepared for the <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commuter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, next week says the average age for the worldwide fleet of turboprops is 11 years old, compared with more than 13 years for passenger jets The study, which groups aircraft by regions of the world, says the North American turboprop fleet is the youngest, while the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> has the oldest aircraft with an average age of 15.4 years. Turboprops in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> average 13.5 years, in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> 13 years, in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> 12.4 years and in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> 12.1 years, according to the report. `` The average age of the commuter-regional turboprop fleet is expected to experience a decline as the operators continue to expand their operations through acquisition of a substantial number of new aircraft in the next decade,'' the report says. It says 68.1 percent of the turboprops in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> were built within the last nine years, while 7.6 percent were built 20 or more years ago. The oldest turboprops are those that carry 40 to 50 passengers, while the youngest are in the 20-39 passenger category. The youngest fleets, according to <ORGANIZATION> Avmark </ORGANIZATION>, belong to the Midway Express system, 3.4 years, and <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commuter </ORGANIZATION>, 3.8 years, while the oldest are operated by <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connector </ORGANIZATION>, 13.2 years, and <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, 12.7 years. Other fleets in the report and the average age of their turboprop planes are <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connection </ORGANIZATION>, 5.6; <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION>, 5.7; <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlink </ORGANIZATION>, 6.5; <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, 6.6; <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, 7.1; TWExpress, 7.9; <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commuter </ORGANIZATION>, 8.1; <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commuter </ORGANIZATION>, 9.0; <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, 10; <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, 10.8, and Canadian Partner, 11. The report covers airplanes in use as of July 1988 and covers those seating 13 passegners or more that were originally designed for passenger use although a few are now being used to haul cargo, <ORGANIZATION> Avmark </ORGANIZATION> said.
