<SECOND>PM-Whittle-Books, Bjt,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Communications Plans To Publish Ad-Sponsored Books</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LP </ORGANIZATION> wants to put short hardcover books by respected authors in the briefcases of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s corporate and civic leaders, and is selling advertising space in the books to pay the bill The proposal disclosed Tuesday stirred curiosity in the publishing community, which has generally limited advertising in hardcover books to pitches for either the author's or the publisher's other works. `` Whether it is a ridiculous idea that will fall on its face or be the wave of the future, I ca n't tell yet,'' said <PERSON> Joni </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, the publisher of <ORGANIZATION> Random </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nansey </PERSON> <PERSON> Neiman </PERSON>, publisher of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION>, said she has n't decided whether advertising in books would be good for business But, she added, `` As a reader, I'm not sure I want to read a book and find an ad for baby powder, or worse.'' The <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, Tenn.-based <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said Tuesday it has signed <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Halberstam </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Galbraith </PERSON> and seven other well-known authors for the first of what it says will be several sponsored book series. It would be the first book publishing venture by the fast-growing media concern, which has specialized in creating magazines, posters and television programs that sponsors may use to reach tightly-defined audiences such as new mothers, pet owners or teens at school. Whittle, which is 50 percent-owned by the media giant <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said it plans to publish the first book in what is tentatively called `` The Larger Agenda'' series later this year. It plans five books a year. The other authors signed by Whittle are <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilder </PERSON>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Atlas </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Waterman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Holbrooke </PERSON>, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Seligman </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Greider </PERSON>. They are reportedly being paid an average of $ 60,000 each. Among the topics, <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON> will write about <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, the indicted junk bond pioneer; <PERSON> Holbrooke </PERSON> will explain why business people should care about foreign policy; and <PERSON> Greider </PERSON> will write about the financial system. The books will run about 100 pages, with 20 pages of advertising scattered among 80 pages of editorial text, and will be sent for free to about 150,000 people Whittle considers opinion leaders. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, said the project resulted from research that showed many readers failed to read or finish books because the books were too long and they had too little time. He said writers, meanwhile, wanted an outlet longer than magazines provide but shorter than full-length books. Advertising support provided the financial bridge needed to support the shorter books, he said. <PERSON> Greider </PERSON>, reached in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said liked getting a `` chance to reach what should be a pretty blue-chip audience'' and had no problem with the type of advertising he expects would be included in the series. `` If the book was studded with truss ads and hair-restoring ads and breast implant ads, I could see how you might have some problems with it,'' he said. Whittle plans to sell copies at bookstores nationwide six months after the free distribution and will sell them more cheaply than books without ads. Whittle officials declined to identify advertisers, but a source familiar with the plans, speaking on condition of anonymity, said <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, will be the sole advertiser in the first series. <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said that for competitive reasons, the company does not comment on its advertising plans. <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Reidy </PERSON>, president and publisher of <ORGANIZATION> Avon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION>, said paperbacks once routinely carried ads two decades ago but the practice was phased out because of postal regulations and protests from authors. `` I do n't think there will be a rush to do it again,'' she said. <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said he hoped to be publishing up to 40 books a year generating $ 50 million in annual revenue for his company in five years. The company had $ 150 million in revenue last year.
