<HEAD>Drexel To Sell Retail Brokerage Unit As Part Of Major Restructuring</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead, 19th graf to CORRECT number of workers; PICKS UP
`Individuals prefer...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stung by bad publicity from the government's massive securities fraud probes and slumping business since the 1987 stock market crash, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is shedding its 2,300-employee retail brokerage unit as part of a major restructuring The nation's fifth-largest investment firm said Tuesday it will try to sell the brokerage unit, which accounts for about 10 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s business, to another brokerage house. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> said it also is abandoning its business in municipal securities, over-the-counter stocks, and research and transactions in non-U.S. securities. The restructuring will cut <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s work force by about a third. The move comes five days after <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> agreed to tight federal oversight for three years in settling civil fraud charges with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> Chief Executive <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> announced the restructuring over the firm's public address system, calling the verdict by its board of directors last weekend `` the only economically viable solution.'' He said the move was made to so <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> could deal with the `` current realities'' at the firm, implying the government's nearly three-year investigation of alleged securities abuses, many involving the <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s dealings with jailed inside trader <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>. `` The decision was made in view of the anticipated inability to grow the retail business to an economically viable size in light of ongoing adverse publicity ...,'' <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> pact clears the way for settlement of criminal fraud charges with the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to plead guilty to six felonies and pay a record $ 650 million to avoid a massive racketeering indictment. A rash of civil lawsuits over <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s activities, possibly numbering in the thousands, now are expected to be filed in individual states. In addition, congressional officials have indicated they plan further investigations into <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. The continued investigations, along with the possible high-visibility trial of former <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> junk-bond financier <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, means the firm will remain in a negative spotlight for some time. `` It's a kind of situation that's very sensitive as far as retail clients are concerned,'' said <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> analyst <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> McCoy </PERSON>. In its statement, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> cited `` the depressed state of the securities industry, the anticipated lack of participation by individual investors'' and increased competition from commercial banks in retail brokerage. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, which does not release earnings or other detailed financial data, said it has total capital of about $ 2 billion and net equity capital of about half that. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON> declined to give details on the extent of the retail business decline, but said: `` It was just getting difficult. Indeed, the numbers were going in the other direction.'' After a board meeting Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGAN