<HEAD>Oil Futures Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices surged in early trading today as concern spread that a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil explosion could disrupt petroleum deliveries. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the May contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, had jumped $ 1.21 a barrel to $ 22.72 at about 11 a.m. EDT. The contract closed at $ 21.51 on Tuesday. `` Details are still vague but there's a possibility that some companies are n't able to deliver on cargos due a week from today,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, energy broker with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` This is impacting the market in a very big way.'' The explosion and fire on the small oil Cormorant Alpha platform owned by <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.K. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> and Production on Tuesday shut down the North Sea Brent oil field, interrupting production of nearly 500,000 barrels a day of oil, officials said today. `` The Cormorant is a gathering station. The Brent crude must flow through this one smaller station,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, oil analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> officials were expected to examine the damage today and decide how long the pipelines would remain closed, analysts said. Energy brokers said the timing of the event, following the Alaskan oil spill, could drive prices significantly higher. The spill off the Alaskan coast on March 24 closed down oil shipping lanes and disrupted the flow of oil to refineries in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for several days. Since then, prices of both crude and refined products have risen by more than 10 cents. Crude prices have risen nearly 80 percent since last October when the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries decided to reduce oil production. In addition, problems with other <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil facilities and lower production by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have helped push prices higher.
