<SECOND>PM-Commodities Rules, 1st Ld-Writethru,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merc Announces Recommendations of Panel in Wake of Federal Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with announcement of recommendations. Adds byline.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> panel today recommended restrictions on most forms of `` dual trading,'' the doubling of its surveillance staff and improved auditing in response to a federal fraud investigation. `` Some of these proposals were under study prior to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation. But the failure to respond quickly would have shown a lack of leadership,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Geldermann </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to Review Trading Practices. <ORGANIZATION> Geldermann </ORGANIZATION> also is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION>, to whom the recommendations are submitted for a decision expected within 60 days. Dual trading enables a trader on the exchange to deal for his own account as well as customers' accounts. While the practice is legal, many consider it a problem because it allows traders to allocate profitable deals to their own accounts and dump losing trades on customers. Proponents argue that dual trading increases liquidity because traders can continue doing business when they do n't have outside orders. But the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> committee, recognizing the public perception that the practice trading invites abuse, recommended dual trading be banned from futures contracts in cases where market volume is great enough to ensure liquidity. The panel also recommended the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>'s fulltime floor surveillance team be doubled from four to eight staff members and said the exchange's disciplinary committees should include a person who is not a <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> member. `` It's hardly cynical to say that they're hoping to act in advance of the government,'' <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview a day before the recommendations were formally released. `` Frankly, I suspect the leadership at the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> is upset by some of the revelations coming out of the probe. Remember also that the futures industry has prospered with self-regulation and they would like to keep control,'' <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> added. The nine-member committee was appointed in late January, following disclosure the federal government was investigating allegations that as many as 100 brokers at the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> systematically cheated investors out of millions of dollars through illegal trading practices. Although as many as 200 subpeonas reportedly have been issued to traders and firms at the world's two largest futures exchanges, no indictments have been issued thus far. Among the members of the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> committee are <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON>, chairman of the executive committee of the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> and special counsel to the exchange's <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION>; and <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, who formerly headed the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the federal agency that regulates the industry. Shortly after it was assembled, the committee asked <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilmouth </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, to assist in its review of trading practices. The <ORGANIZATION> NFA </ORGANIZATION> is the industry's chief watchdog organization. The exchanges have successfully fought off repeated attempts for increased regulation in the past, most recently after the 1987 stock market crash. At the time, some critics blamed the futures exchanges for market volatility that may have worsened the crash. But the exchanges, in a successful effort to forestall more government intervention, argued that futures selling actually provided an outlet that prevented the crash from getting worse.
</TEXT>
