<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Firmer On Rising Oil Prices, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar closed higher on Wednesday against most of the major currencies in European trading, boosted by rising oil prices. Gold prices were mixed. Foreign exchange dealers said higher oil prices and portfolio adjustments by dealers after the dollar's decline on Tuesday lifted the dollar. They said oil price rise encouraged speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would be more likely than the central banks in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to encourage higher interest rates in response to inflationary pressures. However, one dealer in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> said he did n't expect to see the dollar much stronger because recent government reports have indicated weakness in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy, a development that would discourage credit-tightening by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>. The benchmark price of oil from the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>'s Brent field was marked up WEdnesday by $ 1.48 to $ 21.13 a barrel for delivery next month, after news that the entire field had been shut down by a platform gas explosion. The field produces nearly one-quarter of the British sector's ouput of around 2 million barrels daily. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.7113 late Wednesday from $ 1.7185 late Tuesday. Other late rates for the dollar in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with Tuesday's late rates, included: 1.8615 West German marks, up from 1.8528; 1.6360 Swiss francs, up from 1.6283; 6.3025 French francs, up from 6.2750; 2.0985 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0935; 1,363.75 Italian lire, down from 1,366.95; and 1.1865 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1848. Earlier in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 131.88 Japanese yen, down from 132.10 yen late Tuesday. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar traded at 132.10 yen. In the bullion markets, gold traded at a bid of $ 383.95 a troy ounce in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, up from $ 383.25 late Tuesday. But the late bid price for gold fell to $ 383.50 an ounce in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> from $ 384.00 late Tuesday. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 384.25 an ounce, down from $ 386.68 late Tuesday. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid of $ 5.79 a troy ounce, up from $ 5.78 late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
