<HEAD>Bristol-Myers, Other Pharmaceutical Concerns, Post Healthy Profit
Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bristol-Myers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, maker of many widely known brands including Bufferin and Excedrin pain relievers and <ORGANIZATION> Clairol </ORGANIZATION> hair care products, Wednesday reported its first-quarter profit rose 12.6 percent to a record level. Two other companies in the pharmaceutical business _ <ORGANIZATION> Squibb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Schering-Plough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ also posted healthy earnings for the quarter. Bristol-Myers said after-tax earnings amounted to $ 237 million, or 82 cents a share, in the three months ended March 31, up from $ 210.6 million, or 73 cents a share, in 1988's first quarter. Sales for the quarter were the highest in the company's history, rising just over 5 percent to $ 1.60 billion from $ 1.52 billion. International sales gained 11 percent while domestic sales were up 3 percent. Bristol-Myers, based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, has operations in non-prescription and prescription drugs, toiletries and household products, such as Windex and Drano. It did not provide any specific information about the financial performance of its individual operations. Industry analysts have said Bristol-Myers has been a leader in manufacturing anti-cancer drugs and has benefited from the popularity of its anti-anxiety agent, BuSpar. Squibb said its first-quarter earnings rose 17.2 percent to $ 106.5 million, or $ 1.09 a share, from $ 90.9 million, or 89 cents a share, a year earlier. Sales increased 11 percent to $ 662.7 million from $ 596.9 million. The <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>, N.J.-based company's chairman and chief executive officer, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Furland </PERSON>, said the balance sheet improvements reflected excellent performances by <PERSON> Squibb </PERSON>'s leading products, better gross margins and a slight leverage on operating expenses. These positive factors more than compensated for a 23 percent rise in research and development costs and flat sales growth in traditional products. <ORGANIZATION> Schering-Plough </ORGANIZATION> said its net income rose 23.8 percent in the first quarter to $ 125.7 million, or $ 1.12 a share, from $ 101.5 million, or 91 cents a share, the year before. Sales increased 10.5 percent to $ 831.8 million from $ 752.5 million. <ORGANIZATION> Schering-Plough </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, attributed the overall growth mainly to sales in its pharmaceutical businesses, which expanded 14 percent. Sales of <ORGANIZATION> Schering-Plough </ORGANIZATION>'s consumer products, such as Coppertone sun protection products and Dr. <PERSON> Scholl </PERSON>'s foot care line, rose more modestly. Among the products pacing the increase in pharmaceutical sales were items to treat asthma, cardiovascular problems and dermatological disorders, <ORGANIZATION> Schering-Plough </ORGANIZATION> said.
