<HEAD>Soybean, Corn Futures Drop On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn and soybean futures prices closed with steep losses Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> following midday forecasts for an increased chance of rain in the western Corn Belt later this week. But wheat futures advanced on persistent talk of hot, dry weather in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and on news that <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> is seeking to buy 300,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at subsidized prices. `` Welcome to the weather market,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, a grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, referring to the recent volatility in the grain markets. Some private meteorologists who had been predicting dry weather for the rest of this week in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and northwestern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> forecast rain in their noon forecasts on Wednesday, prompting heavy selling of corn and soybean contracts. The markets are unusually sensitive to weather forecasts because last year's drought lowered <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain stockpiles. Another drought year could drain stocks down to critical levels. At the close, wheat was unchanged to 4 -RCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in May at $ 4.11 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 2 -LCB- cents to 4 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 2.73 a bushel; oats were 1 \ cents to 3 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 1.97 a bushel; soybeans were 3 -LCB- cents to 11 cents lower with May at $ 7.45 a bushel
