<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Dell Adv23   04-19 0964</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Dell, Adv 23,0996</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, April 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Computer Clonemaster Faces Wrath of Wall Street</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dell </PERSON> _ 24-year-old college-dropout whiz kid multimillionaire who made his fortune cloning computers _ has a problem, he says. Wall Street does n't understand his 5-year-old company. Financial analysts are n't sure <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dell </PERSON> understands business. <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> wowed Wall Street by taking a company from startup to $ 257.8 million in annual sales and $ 14.4 million in profit by selling copies of the popular <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> personal computers. <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> carted three computers off to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> in 1984, promptly sold them at a profit and began making clones in his condominium near the campus. Soon he was earning up to $ 80,000 a month and figured computers, not classrooms, were where he should direct his attention. Not bad for a pre-med major who began tinkering with computers in high school and used to hang out at the local Radio Shack store in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> begging his orthodontist father for a PC. Success in the muddled <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> clone market brought <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> much favorable publicity in financial and trade publications. He was labeled an `` innovation upstart,'' `` computer industry's latest whiz kid'' and `` entrepreneur in short pants.'' But <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION>'s gimmick was marketing, not technology. He bypassed retailers, going directly to consumers through advertisements in user magazines and selling his wares over the phone from <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>. Then last year, <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> ran into a $ 104 million inventory buildup and the bitter departure of a senior vice president. The buildup knocked revenue and sales predictions askew. Even <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the investment firms that helped with last year's initial public offering, now is telling customers to buy another computer stock instead. After an initial price of $ 8.50 per share, the stock climbed to $ 13, but fell to $ 6 after the problems became apparent. It currently is hanging around $ 7. The problems shifted the headlines, in <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION>'s own words, `` from whiz kid to fizz kid.'' One publication called him `` the enfant terrible of personal computers.'' `` We think the perception of the company is quite different than what's going on here,'' <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> said, describing his company as `` a new, unique and different kind of entity ... we have merged a design and manufacturing operation for computers together into an entity.'' But even <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> admits there were problems, although he attributes them to success-caused malfunctions that have been fixed. `` I think the stock market is going to wait until it sees tangible proof that <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> is turning around,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Benton </PERSON>, who follows <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> for <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION>. `` The balance sheet has eroded; margins have eroded,'' <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> `` has phenomenal long-term prospects,'' he said, but the market focuses on immediate gratification. To explain his problems, <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> draws diagrams on a note pad to demonstrate how a backlog of orders in the second quarter of the year inflated third quarter sales, which in turn caused forecasters to expect unrealistic fourth quarter production. At the same time, <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> was anticipating huge fourth quarter sales based on a barrage of favorable reviews in computer magazines. The sales did n't reach expectations, saddling the company with a large _ and in some cases high-priced _ inventory. `` I think he's right that the backlog issue created too high expectations,'' <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> admitted, but added, `` If overlooking that made us have high expectations, he did it too.'' Much like a chastised teen-ager promising he has changed, <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> says his company has learned from the past, with a new structure and some new managers. `` The best thing I could do for the company is to find the best people and give them the responsibility to do the job,'' he said during an interview in his penthouse office in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>'s exclusive Arboretum business park. <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> describes his workers, who average about 27 years old, as `` 1,200 totally fired up, foaming at the mouth employees.'' He often points to <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, vice president of research and development. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, 47, came from <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s nearby laboratory in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, where he helped the giant develop its Unix program for PCs. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> is trying to turn the company to more technological innovation, and <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> holds two of its own patents with more pending. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> replaced <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Beachum </PERSON>, hired on at <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> from <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Beachum </PERSON> left last year following a bitter dispute with <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> over most areas of the business <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> said the blowup `` hurt the entire company, hurt me, hurt <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, hurt the employees here,'' but <PERSON> Beachum </PERSON> had to go because `` clearly we had a guy here who was not the right guy.'' For his part, <PERSON> Beachum </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Week </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> that <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> was unwilling to spend money building a sales force, and that <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION>'s plan for a Personal System-2 clone was `` ego-driven. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> since has scrapped those plans, and <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> says he learned he should n't announce products before they're ready to be shipped. In the reorganization, <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> established separate subsidiaries for domestic and overseas clients. Within <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> are divisions for small customers, principally individuals and small businesses; larger businesses; potential customers in government and education; and resellers. In the meantime, <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> enjoys his riches _ he owns 10.7 million shares of the company, even after selling 300,000 shares at about $ 11 per share, or $ 3.3 million. Though <ORGANIZATION> Dell </ORGANIZATION> says his job `` is not what I would consider work,'' he does not consider himself the stereotypical yuppie obsessed with the quest for riches and is planning to marry in a few months. `` I work a fairly normal set of hours for a busy person like myself,'' he says. `` I take a good number of vacations to make sure that I'm well-prepared to do my job.''
</TEXT>
