<HEAD>Earnings Fall in 2nd-Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ralston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Purina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday said its second-quarter earnings slipped 2.7 percent from last year's results that included a contribution from its Van Camp Seafood operations which have since been sold Net earnings for the quarter ended March 31 amounted to $ 90.8 million, or $ 1.39 a share, compared with earnings of $ 93.3 million, or $ 1.35 a share, a year earlier. Second-quarter revenue rose 14.3 percent to $ 1.6 billion from $ 1.4 billion for the same period last year. The company said its Van Camp operations accounted for $ 4.6 million in net earnings in the second quarter last year. For the first six months of its fiscal year, <ORGANIZATION> Ralston </ORGANIZATION> said its net earnings rose 30.1 percent to $ 293.5 million, or $ 4.44 a share, compared with net earnings of $ 225.7 million, or $ 3.25 a share, a year earlier. Six-month revcenue rose 12 percent to $ 3.27 billion from $ 2.92 billion for the same period last year. Operating profit in the human foods and pet foods operation increased this year over last year, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s operating profit was down for the quarter due to lower cake volume. But for the six months, higher bread volume kept <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s operating profit even with last year. Operating profit for the quarter and the six months for <ORGANIZATION> Eveready </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Battery </ORGANIZATION> was down as a result of heavy advertising and promotional spending, the company said.
