<HEAD>Microsoft Makes A Profit After All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> earnings rose 10 percent in the latest quarter, the personal computer software maker said Wednesday, belying its own forecast of an earnings decline. <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> rival <ORGANIZATION> Ashton-Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported a small earnings gain, while <ORGANIZATION> Wang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> predicted it would post the worst quarterly loss in two years in its third fiscal quarter. <PERSON> Redmond </PERSON>, Wash.-based <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> said it earned $ 41.1 million, or 73 cents per share, in the third fiscal quarter ended March 31, up from $ 37.3 million, or 67 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 22 percent to $ 197 million from $ 161.8 million a year earlier. For the first nine months of its fiscal year, <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings rose 33.3 percent to $ 184.1 million, or $ 2.23 a share, from $ 140.9 million, or $ 1.68 a share, a year earlier Revenue rose 38.8 percent to $ 583.3 million from $ 420.4 million a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>'s stock plunged last month when the company predicted an earnings decline, the first such drop since the company went public three years ago. Some shareholders complained last month that they were n't adequately warned about the company's difficulties Now it turns out that the warnings were overstated. March results turned out better than expected, according to <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> Edstrom </PERSON>, a spokeswoman at <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>'s public relations firm. `` At least this news was better than the other news,'' she said. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON>, Mass.-based <ORGANIZATION> Wang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> said it expects to lose some $ 55 million in its third quarter. Last week, <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> announced plans to drop its worldwide payroll to 28,500 by June 1990. It had 31,700 employees in November, when it began a policy of not filling vacancies. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> plans to release its actual earnings figure Friday, two days behind schedule. In a statement released Wednesday, the computer manufacturer said unit sales and total revenues will be `` approximately equal'' to that of the previous quarter and the third quarter of fiscal 1988. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>'s sales totalled $ 767.9 million a year ago and $ 760.7 million in 1989's second quarter. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> blamed this quarter's loss on increased discounting of product sales, lower maintentance revenue in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and a shift to lower-margin sales of personal computers. The firm's main business is minicomputers The firm has followed 1988's $ 92 million gain with disappointing profits of $ 13.1 million and $ 1 million the first two quarters of this fiscal year. <ORGANIZATION> Ashton-Tate </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Torrance </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said its net income rose to $ 11.5 million, or 44 cents a share, from $ 11.1 million, or 43 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $ 89.8 million from $ 72.4 million a year earlier. The company attributed the flat earnings to increased research and development and sales and marketing expenses.
