<HEAD>Pickens Says Corporate Buyouts Will Find Their Way into Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American takeover specialist <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said Wednesday that corporate buyouts helped invigorate the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy in the 1980s, and similar tactics will find their way into Japanese business in the 1990s. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for talks with management of <ORGANIZATION> Koito </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> after buying 20.2 percent of its shares _ a move he said was not a prelude to a takeover attempt or greenmail. `` We want to work with <ORGANIZATION> Koito </ORGANIZATION> managment. We are n't doing anything hostile,'' he said, adding that he was investing for `` the long term.'' Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Koito </ORGANIZATION>, which expressed surprise and concern at the time of <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>' purchase, announced Wednesday evening that it was transferring the shares to <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>' ownership, dropping a request to the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> to investigate whether there were any technical irregularities that might block the purchase. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> is scheduled to meet Thursday with the president of the company, said a company spokesman. At a luncheon Wednesday with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> argued that corporate buyouts helped put the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy back on its feet in the 1980s by ousting ineffective management and making its companies more competitive. `` What happened in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> in the 1980s will find its way to the Japanese business community in the 1990s,'' he said. Analysts in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> say <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>' visit is a challenge to basic thinking in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s business community that a company belongs to its employees, not its shareholders. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> gained fame and fortune in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by buying and reorganizing companies and often purging company executives, arguing that bad managers do n't give shareholders the returns they deserve. He said in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> Wednesday that his `` shareholders' rights'' movement would soon spread to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` Shareholders rights will become a worldwide issue,'' he added. But many Japanese businessmen, and some foreign critics, believe that the American emphasis on return to shareholders has caused <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies to lose competitiveness to Japanese companies. `` Japanese companies do n't generally have to answer to shareholders with short-term profits. They can focus on longer-term growth. Just look at these two economies to see which approach has been more successful,'' said <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Koito </ORGANIZATION> makes headlights and other parts for <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 19.1 percent of the company <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>' shares are worth about $ 1 billion at current market prices. Despite <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>' denial, `` many people think it is greenmail,'' <PERSON> Shigeju </PERSON> <PERSON> Kita </PERSON>, general manager in charge of mergers and acquisitions at <ORGANIZATION> Yamaichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, said of <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>' stock purchase. Greenmail is a premium paid by a company to buy back stock from an unwanted suitor. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> says he is challenging barriers to foreign investment in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and many Americans are cheering him on. `` I am concerned that American investors do n't have the same access in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> as Japanese have in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said he could not judge how open or closed the Japanese market was until he saw the results of his present enterprise. But he added that `` people in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> are watching this carefully. ... Japan-bashers ... will come to the surface pretty quick'' if they think that an American company is being unfairly treated in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, he said. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> told the American Chamber audience he was considering running for governor of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Later, he told reporters that the <ORGANIZATION> Koito </ORGANIZATION> deal `` was not done with political motives in mind, but I've had people suggest it might be an advantage in a political race.''
</TEXT>
