<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     04-19 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0146</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices pushed ahead today, getting a little more mileage out of the rally that has carried the market to its highest levels since the crash of 1987. Analysts said stocks have drawn support in recent days from spreading hopes that inflationary pressures might be easing and interest rates were turning downward. Inflation figures for March, unlike those for the two previous months, contained no unpleasant surprises that seemed likely to prompt the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to tighten credit further. Signs of a slowing economy also raise some new worries for investors. For one thing, some observers suggest, they could lead to heightened concern about the possibility of a recession. However, brokers said, any such fears were countered today by strong earnings reports from several prominent companies.
</TEXT>
