<HEAD>Big First-Quarter Profit Drop Blamed on Earlier Tax Benefit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s profit plunged in the first quarter, but the decline was attributed to a huge one-time tax benefit in the comparable quarter a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>, which has been rocked by a series of allegations of overbilling and a defense fraud indictment, said Wednesday its first-quarter profit fell to $ 9.7 million, or 21 cents a share, from $ 139.6 million, or $ 2.97 a share in the first quarter of 1988. The difference was the result of a one-time gain of $ 135.1 million in the earlier quarter, when the company took advantage of a law that allowed it to defer payment of taxes in earlier years until the new, lower corporate tax rate took effect. Without the tax benefit, earnings in 1988's first quarter would have been $ 4.5 million, or less than half of this year's first-quarter income <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>'s sales in the first quarter were $ 1.28 billion, down 7 percent from $ 1.37 billion a year earlier. The company also took a charge against profits of $ 26 million for unplanned research and development expenses on an electronic defense system for the F-15 fighter jet. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> made a similar provision in the fourth quarter of last year for development of the system, called the ALQ-135, but did n't reveal the amount of the write-off for that quarter Overall sales declined for several reasons: Less Pentagon money for research and development of the B-2 stealth bomber, which is moving into production; fewer MX missile sales; and fewer deliveries of fuselages for the FA-18 Hornet fighter, which is built by <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. The sales declines were partly offset by an increase in deliveries of 747 airliner fuselages to <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> has been the target of several lawsuits by employee `` whistleblowers'' who allege the company overcharged the government on various projects The corporation and five present and former employees were charged this month with conspiracy and fraud in an alleged scheme to fake tests on a device used to guide cruise missiles. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> denies any wrongdoing.
