<HEAD>Dollar Firmer On Rising Oil Prices; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar bounced back Wednesday from its decline of the previous session, boosted by higher oil prices. Foreign exchange dealers said the rise in the dollar was amplified by purchases by traders who had been betting on its continued decline and had to buy dollars to cover short positions. Oil futures prices spurted to a three-year high Wednesday after a North Sea gas explosion and an industry report that showed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production falling to its lowest level since the 1960s. The rise in oil prices increased inflation fears, raising the possibility that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would tighten credit to stop inflation. Tight credit attracts global investors to dollars. A government inflation report had lowered the dollar on Tuesday by diminishing the likelihood of credit-tightening by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>. Wednesday's higher oil prices lowered the Japanese yen against the dollar because <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> depends on imported oil. The yen was also hurt by an unfounded rumor that Japanese Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> had resigned, according to <PERSON> Nazem </PERSON> <PERSON> Elsabeh </PERSON>, a trader and vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.7113 late Wednesday from $ 1.7185 late Tuesday. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the pound fell to $ 1.7108 from $ 1.7164. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 131.88 Japanese yen, down from 132.10 yen late Tuesday. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar traded at 132.10 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar rose to 132.58 yen from 131.40 on Wednesday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with Tuesday's late rates, included: 1.8623 West German marks, up from 1.8525; 1.6373 Swiss francs, up from 1.6270; 1.1858 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1863; 6.3040 French francs, up from 6.2710; and 1,364.38 Italian lire, up from 1,360.13 Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with Tuesday's rates: 1.8615 West German marks, up from 1.8528; 1.6360 Swiss francs, up from 1.6283; 6.3025 French francs, up from 6.2750; 2.0985 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0935; 1,363.75 Italian lire, down from 1,366.95; and 1.1865 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1848. In the bullion markets, prices were narrowly mixed. Gold closed in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> at $ 384.25 an ounce, down from $ 386.68 late Tuesday. Gold traded at a late bid of $ 383.95 a troy ounce in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, up from $ 383.25 late Tuesday. But the late bid price for gold fell to $ 383.50 an ounce in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> from $ 384.00 late Tuesday. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery fell to $ 383.40 an ounce from $ 383.50 on Wednesday. Later, <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold was bid at $ 382.80 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $ 383.10 late Wednesday. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid of $ 5.79 a troy ounce, up from $ 5.78 late Tuesday. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery fell to $ 5.750 an ounce from $ 5.763 on Wednesday.
