<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Slide On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices for corn and soybeans to be harvested this fall fell sharply Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> on forecasts for rain later this week in the western Corn Belt, a key growing area hit hard by last summer's drought. Wheat futures prices rose due to persistent dryness in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, where the winter wheat crop already has sustained severe damage. On other markets, oil futures posted steep gains, livestock and meat futures prices tumbled and precious metals were slightly lower. Wheat settled unchanged to 4 -RCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in May at $ 4.11 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 2 -LCB- cents to 4 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 2.73 a bushel; oats were 1 \ cents to 2 -RCB- cents lower with May at $ 1.97 a bushel; soybeans were 3 -LCB- cents to 11 \ cents lower with May at $ 7.45 a `` Welcome to the weather market,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, a New York-based grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, referring to the recent volatility in the grain markets. Corn and soybean planting has barely begun but the grain markets are extremely sensitive to weather changes because last year's drought lowered <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain stockpiles Another drought year could drain stocks down to critical levels and cause prices to skyrocket. Some private meteorologists who had been predicting dry weather for the rest of this week in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and northwestern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> put more rain into their noon forecasts on Wednesday, prompting heavy selling of corn and soybean contracts. After the close, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> issued a new six-to-10 day forecast calling for above-normal rainfall in the western <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and normal precipitation in the region's central and eastern portions, which could prompt further selling of corn and soybean futures on Thursday. `` The irony is that most experts agree that beyond 72 hours, the degree of accuracy in a forecast drops geometrically,'' <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> said, `` and yet everybody pays attention to those forecasts because there is n't anything else to trade on.'' Unleaded gasoline prices surged on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, leading the crude oil and heating oil markets higher, following Tuesday's <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> report of substantial reductions in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supplies of crude and gasoline. Further buying was spurred by reports that the <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s British subsidiary had advise clients of possible shipment delays for <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> crude oil following the shutdown late Tuesday of a damaged oil platform West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents to $ 1.10 higher with May at $ 22.61 a barrel; heating oil was .53 cent to .71 cent higher with May at 53.33 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .75 cent to 1.20 cents higher with May at 74.62 cents a gallon. The sharp losses in livestock and meat futures on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> were due more to profit-taking and technical factors than to Wednesday's weaker cash markets, analysts said. Trading activity has grown cautious ahead of Friday's quarterly <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> cattle-on-feed report, which is expected to show first-quarter placements of cattle on feedlots to be 3 percent to 10 percent above the first quarter of 1988. Live cattle settled .10 cent to 1.02 cents lower with June at 70.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .57 cent to .97 cent lower with May at 75.55 cents a pound; live hogs were .25 cent to .80 cent lower with June at 45.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.05 cents to 1.88 cents lower with May at 31.57 cents a pound. Gold and silver futures prices inched lower on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Investment demand for the metals has fallen following government economic reports that indicate the economy is slowing and inflation is holding steady. Gold settled 10 cents to 60 cents lower with June at $ 387.10 a troy ounce; silver was 1.3 cents to 1.5 cents lower with May at $ 5.765 a troy ounce.
