e to rebuild to a smaller level without the fractious pilots returning to work. The airline will need an estimated 1,500 pilots to run 60 percent of its previous operations. Of the 3,600 or so Eastern pilots, only 200 have crossed picket lines. `` We can train pilots at a very substantial rate,'' <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> said. He disputed the pilots union's claim of a nationwide pilot shortage. Asked whether a sharply reduced Eastern would be viable, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> said, `` We believe it -LRB- would be -RRB- but there are no guarantees in this world.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> chief also refuted earlier statements by attorneys for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and the pilots union that another potential buyer had emerged besides <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>, hotelier <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON> and takeover strategist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>. `` There is no serious fourth bidder,'' <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> said. He insisted there are no talks currently between his company and potential suitors. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> had called him Tuesday and made it `` very plain that he's out of the deal.'' Sources close to <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>, however, said Wednesday the two men have continued negotiating by telephone. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, the pilots' attorney, insisted Wednesday that the fourth bidding group has met with <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, the bankruptcy examiner for Eastern. `` They are putting together their bid,'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said. A source close to the situation, who asked not to be identified, called the fourth bidder `` a serious and substantial presence.'' Workers struck the nation's seventh-largest carrier March 4 in a longstanding dispute with <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, accusing him of dismembering <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGA