<HEAD>AMR Quarterly Profit Up 47.7 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, parent company of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, reported Wednesday a 47.7 percent jump in first-quarter profit, partly due to increased traffic as passengers looked for an alternative to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. Net earnings were $ 101 million, or $ 1.60 per share, on revenues of $ 2.45 billion during the quarter. That compares with earnings of $ 68.4 million, or $ 1.12 per share, on revenues of $ 1.97 billion in the same quarter last year. The first-quarter 1989 earnings included a $ 14.1 million gain from the sale of certain property rights, the company said. American's load factor at <LOCATION> Raleigh-Durham </LOCATION> airport in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> jumped from 63 percent in last year's first quarter to 71.2 percent this year, while in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, the factor rose from 70.3 to 81.4, <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Crandall </PERSON> said. Both locations were Eastern strongholds. Eastern filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection March 9 after its Machinists union members went on strike, crippling the airline. American's revenue passenger miles, a key industry statistic, rose 9.7 percent in the quarter, from 14.77 million in the year-ago period to 16.2 million.
</TEXT>
