<HEAD>NCR Shareholders Reject South African Pullout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NCR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> shareholders Wednesday rejected a proposal to entirely withdraw the company's operations from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NCR </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors had urged shareholders to vote against the proposal at Wednesday's annual meeting. The company announced April 4 that it plans to sell its South African subsidiary and market its products through a distributor in that nation. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NCR </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president and secretary, wrote shareholders a letter saying that if the planned South African transaction can not be completed, there is no assurance that the board could enter into another agreement that would similarly serve shareholder interests. Former Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> retired from the board following Wednesday's meeting. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, who reached the company's mandatory retirement age of 70, had served on the board since his appointment as <ORGANIZATION> NCR </ORGANIZATION>'s president in 1972 The Dayton-based company makes and sells business information processing systems for worldwide markets.
