<HEAD>Wells Fargo Reaches Agreement With Hong Kong Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Hongkong'' and ``HongkongBank'' are cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday it will expand the international services available to its customers through an agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Hongkong </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shanghai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. At the same time, the San Francisco-based banking concern will dispose of its four remaining overseas offices in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> In an effort to concentrate on its core market in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> has been reducing its direct involvement in overseas activity except for the area of trade financing. <ORGANIZATION> HongkongBank </ORGANIZATION> will serve <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> customers outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and will take over its business and office in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. It also will help dispose of <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> office, the company said. The <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> offices of <ORGANIZATION> HongkongBank </ORGANIZATION> will also refer their retail banking business to <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION>. However, the offices will retain their corporate customers in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reichardt </PERSON> termed the agreement with <ORGANIZATION> HongkongBank </ORGANIZATION> `` the first of its kind for a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank and a forerunner of how global banking will be done in the 1990s.''
</TEXT>
